\fBLSB_DISABLE_LIMLOCK_EXCL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSB_DISABLE_LIMLOCK_EXCL=y | n
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If preemptive scheduling is enabled, this parameter enables
   preemption of and preemption by exclusive jobs when
   \fBPREEMPT_JOBTYPE\fR=EXCLUSIVE in lsb.params. Changing this
   parameter requires a restart of all sbatchds in the cluster
   (badmin hrestart). Do not change this parameter while
   exclusive jobs are running.
.sp 2
   When \fBLSB_DISABLE_LIMLOCK_EXCL=y\fR, for a host running an
   exclusive job:
.sp 2
     o  
         LIM is not locked on a host running an exclusive job
.sp 2
     o  
         lsload displays the host status ok.
.sp 2
     o  
         bhosts displays the host status closed.
.sp 2
     o  
         Users can run tasks on the host using lsrun or lsgrun.
         To prevent users from running tasks during execution of
         an exclusive job, the parameter
         \fBLSF_DISABLE_LSRUN\fR=y must be defined in lsf.conf.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   n. LSF locks the LIM on a host running an exclusive job and
   unlocks the LIM when the exclusive job finishes.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_DISABLE_RERUN_POST_EXEC\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_DISABLE_RERUN_POST_EXEC=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, and the job is rerunnable, the POST_EXEC configured at
   the job level or the queue level is not executed if the job is
   rerun.
.sp 2
   Running of post-execution commands upon restart of a
   rerunnable job may not always be desirable. For example, if
   the post-exec removes certain files, or does other cleanup
   that should only happen if the job finishes successfully, use
   LSB_DISABLE_RERUN_POST_EXEC to prevent the post-exec from
   running and allow the successful continuation of the job when
   it reruns.
.sp 2
   The POST_EXEC may still run for a job rerun when the execution
   host loses contact with the master host due to network
   problems. In this case mbatchd assumes the job has failed and
   restarts the job on another host. The original execution host,
   out of contact with the master host, completes the job and
   runs the POST_EXEC.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_ECHKPNT_KEEP_OUTPUT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_ECHKPNT_KEEP_OUTPUT=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Saves the standard output and standard error of custom echkpnt
   and erestart methods to:
.sp 2
     o  
         \fRcheckpoint_dir/$LSB_JOBID/echkpnt.out \fR
.sp 2
     o  
         \fRcheckpoint_dir/$LSB_JOBID/echkpnt.err \fR
.sp 2
     o  
         \fRcheckpoint_dir/$LSB_JOBID/erestart.out\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         \fRcheckpoint_dir/$LSB_JOBID/erestart.err\fR
.sp 2
   Can also be defined as an environment variable.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. Standard error and standard output messages from
   custom echkpnt and erestart programs is directed to /dev/null
   and discarded by LSF.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD, LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD="\fR\fImethod_name\fR
   [\fImethod_name\fR] ...\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Name of custom echkpnt and erestart methods.
.sp 2
   Can also be defined as an environment variable, or specified
   through the bsub -k option.
.sp 2
   The name you specify here is used for both your custom echkpnt
   and erestart programs. You must assign your custom echkpnt and
   erestart programs the name \fRechkpnt.\fImethod_name\fR\fR and
   \fRerestart.\fR\fImethod_name\fR. The programs
   \fRechkpnt.\fImethod_name\fR\fR and
   \fRerestart.\fR\fImethod_name\fR. must be in LSF_SERVERDIR or
   in the directory specified by LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR.
.sp 2
   Do not define LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD=default as default is a
   reserved keyword to indicate to use the default echkpnt and
   erestart methods of LSF. You can however, specify bsub -k
   "my_dir method=default" my_job to indicate that you want to
   use the default checkpoint and restart methods.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is not defined in lsf.conf or as an
   environment variable and no custom method is specified at job
   submission through bsub -k, LSF uses echkpnt.default and
   erestart.default to checkpoint and restart jobs.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is defined, LSF uses the custom checkpoint
   and restart methods specified.
.sp 2 .SH "Limitations"
\fBLimitations\fR
.sp 2
   The method name and directory (LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR)
   combination must be unique in the cluster.
.sp 2
   For example, you may have two echkpnt applications with the
   same name such as echkpnt.mymethod but what differentiates
   them is the different directories defined with
   LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR. It is the cluster administrator’s
   responsibility to ensure that method name and method directory
   combinations are unique in the cluster.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF uses echkpnt.default and erestart.default to
   checkpoint and restart jobs
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR, LSB_ECHKPNT_KEEP_OUTPUT
.sp 2
\fBLSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Absolute path name of the directory in which custom echkpnt
   and erestart programs are located.
.sp 2
   The checkpoint method directory should be accessible by all
   users who need to run the custom echkpnt and erestart
   programs.
.sp 2
   Can also be defined as an environment variable.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF searches in LSF_SERVERDIR for custom echkpnt
   and erestart programs.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_ESUB_METHOD, LSB_ECHKPNT_KEEP_OUTPUT
.sp 2
\fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSB_ESUB_METHOD="esub_application [esub_application] ..."
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies a mandatory esub that applies to all job
   submissions. \fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR lists the names of the
   application-specific esub executables used in addition to any
   executables specified by the bsub -a option.
.sp 2
   For example, \fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR="dce fluent" runs
   LSF_SERVERDIR/esub.dce and LSF_SERVERDIR/esub.fluent for all
   jobs submitted to the cluster. These esubs define,
   respectively, DCE as the mandatory security system and FLUENT
   as the mandatory application for all jobs.
.sp 2
   \fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR can also be defined as an environment
   variable.
.sp 2
   The value of \fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR must correspond to an
   actual esub file. For example, to use
   \fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR=fluent, the file esub.fluent must exist
   in LSF_SERVERDIR.
.sp 2
   The name of the esub program must be a valid file name. Valid
   file names contain only alphanumeric characters, underscore
   (\fR_\fR) and hyphen (\fR-\fR).
.sp 2
      \fBRestriction: \fR
.sp 2
         The name esub.user is reserved. Do not use the name
         esub.user for an application-specific esub.
.sp 2
   The master esub (mesub) uses the name you specify to invoke
   the appropriate esub program. The esub and
   esub.\fIesub_application\fR programs must be located in
   LSF_SERVERDIR.
.sp 2
   LSF does not detect conflicts based on esub names. For
   example, if \fBLSB_ESUB_METHOD\fR="openmpi" and \fRbsub -a
   pvm\fR is specified at job submission, the job could fail
   because these esubs define two different types of parallel job
   handling.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF does not apply a mandatory esub to jobs
   submitted to the cluster.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_INTERACT_MSG_ENH\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_INTERACT_MSG_ENH=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, enables enhanced messaging for interactive batch jobs.
   To disable interactive batch job messages, set
   LSB_INTERACT_MSG_ENH to any value other than y or Y; for
   example, LSB_INTERACT_MSG_ENH=N.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_INTERACT_MSG_INTVAL
.sp 2
\fBLSB_INTERACT_MSG_INTVAL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_INTERACT_MSG_INTVAL=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the update interval in seconds for interactive batch
   job messages. LSB_INTERACT_MSG_INTVAL is ignored if
   LSB_INTERACT_MSG_ENH is not set.
.sp 2
   Job information that LSF uses to get the pending or suspension
   reason is updated according to the value of
   PEND_REASON_UPDATE_INTERVAL in \fRlsb.params\fR.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. If LSB_INTERACT_MSG_INTVAL is set to an incorrect
   value, the default update interval is 60 seconds.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_INTERACT_MSG_ENH
.sp 2
\fBLSB_JOBID_DISP_LENGTH\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_JOBID_DISP_LENGTH=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   By default, LSF commands bjobs and bhist display job IDs with
   a maximum length of 7 characters. Job IDs greater than 9999999
   are truncated on the left.
.sp 2
   When LSB_JOBID_DISP_LENGTH=10, the width of the JOBID column
   in bjobs and bhist increases to 10 characters.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Specify an integer between 7 and 10.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF uses the default 7-character length for job
   ID display.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_JOB_CPULIMIT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_JOB_CPULIMIT=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Determines whether the CPU limit is a per-process limit
   enforced by the OS or whether it is a per-job limit enforced
   by LSF:
.sp 2
     o  
         The per-process limit is enforced by the OS when the CPU
         time of one process of the job exceeds the CPU limit.
.sp 2
     o  
         The per-job limit is enforced by LSF when the total CPU
         time of all processes of the job exceed the CPU limit.
.sp 2
   This parameter applies to CPU limits set when a job is
   submitted with bsub -c, and to CPU limits set for queues by
   CPULIMIT in lsb.queues.
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF-enforced per-job limit: When the sum of the CPU time
         of all processes of a job exceed the CPU limit, LSF
         sends a SIGXCPU signal (where supported by the operating
         system) from the operating system to all processes
         belonging to the job, then SIGINT, SIGTERM and SIGKILL.
         The interval between signals is 10 seconds by default.
         The time interval between SIGXCPU, SIGINT, SIGKILL,
         SIGTERM can be configured with the parameter
         JOB_TERMINATE_INTERVAL in lsb.params.
.sp 2
            \fBRestriction: \fR
.sp 2
               SIGXCPU is not supported by Windows.
.sp 2
     o  
         OS-enforced per process limit: When one process in the
         job exceeds the CPU limit, the limit is enforced by the
         operating system. For more details, refer to your
         operating system documentation for setrlimit().
.sp 2
   The setting of LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT has the following effect on
   how the limit is enforced:
.sp 2
      When LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT is
.sp 2
      LSF-enforced per-job limit
.sp 2
      OS-enforced per-process limit
.sp 2
      y
.sp 2
      Enabled
.sp 2
      Disabled
.sp 2
      n
.sp 2
      Disabled
.sp 2
      Enabled
.sp 2
      Not defined
.sp 2
      Enabled
.sp 2
      Enabled
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "Notes"
\fBNotes\fR
.sp 2
   To make LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT take effect, use the command badmin
   hrestart all to restart all sbatchds in the cluster.
.sp 2
   Changing the default Terminate job control action: You can
   define a different terminate action in lsb.queues with the
   parameter JOB_CONTROLS if you do not want the job to be
   killed. For more details on job controls, see Administering
   Platform LSF.
.sp 2 .SH "Limitations"
\fBLimitations\fR
.sp 2
   If a job is running and the parameter is changed, LSF is not
   able to reset the type of limit enforcement for running jobs.
.sp 2
     o  
         If the parameter is changed from per-process limit
         enforced by the OS to per-job limit enforced by LSF
         (LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT=n changed to LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT=y), both
         per-process limit and per-job limit affect the running
         job. This means that signals may be sent to the job
         either when an individual process exceeds the CPU limit
         or the sum of the CPU time of all processes of the job
         exceed the limit. A job that is running may be killed by
         the OS or by LSF.
.sp 2
     o  
         If the parameter is changed from per-job limit enforced
         by LSF to per-process limit enforced by the OS
         (LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT=y changed to LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT=n), the
         job is allowed to run without limits because the
         per-process limit was previously disabled.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   lsb.queues, bsub, JOB_TERMINATE_INTERVAL in lsb.params,
   LSB_MOD_ALL_JOBS
.sp 2
\fBLSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Determines whether the memory limit is a per-process limit
   enforced by the OS or whether it is a per-job limit enforced
   by LSF.
.sp 2
     o  
         The per-process limit is enforced by the OS when the
         memory allocated to one process of the job exceeds the
         memory limit.
.sp 2
     o  
         The per-job limit is enforced by LSF when the sum of the
         memory allocated to all processes of the job exceeds the
         memory limit.
.sp 2
   This parameter applies to memory limits set when a job is
   submitted with bsub -M \fImem_limit\fR, and to memory limits
   set for queues with MEMLIMIT in lsb.queues.
.sp 2
   The setting of LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT has the following effect on
   how the limit is enforced:
.sp 2
      When LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT is
.sp 2
      LSF-enforced per-job limit
.sp 2
      OS-enforced per-process limit
.sp 2
      y
.sp 2
      Enabled
.sp 2
      Disabled
.sp 2
      n or not defined
.sp 2
      Disabled
.sp 2
      Enabled
.sp 2
   When LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT is Y, the LSF-enforced per-job limit is
   enabled, and the OS-enforced per-process limit is disabled.
.sp 2
   When LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT is N or not defined, the LSF-enforced
   per-job limit is disabled, and the OS-enforced per-process
   limit is enabled.
.sp 2
   \fILSF-enforced per-job limit\fR: When the total memory
   allocated to all processes in the job exceeds the memory
   limit, LSF sends the following signals to kill the job:
   SIGINT, SIGTERM, then SIGKILL. The interval between signals is
   10 seconds by default.
.sp 2
   On UNIX, the time interval between SIGINT, SIGKILL, SIGTERM
   can be configured with the parameter JOB_TERMINATE_INTERVAL in
   lsb.params.
.sp 2
   \fIOS-enforced per process limit\fR: When the memory allocated
   to one process of the job exceeds the memory limit, the
   operating system enforces the limit. LSF passes the memory
   limit to the operating system. Some operating systems apply
   the memory limit to each process, and some do not enforce the
   memory limit at all.
.sp 2
   OS memory limit enforcement is only available on systems that
   support RLIMIT_RSS for setrlimit().
.sp 2
   The following operating systems do not support the memory
   limit at the OS level and the job is allowed to run without a
   memory limit:
.sp 2
     o  
         Windows
.sp 2
     o  
         Sun Solaris 2.x
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. Per-process memory limit enforced by the OS;
   per-job memory limit enforced by LSF disabled
.sp 2 .SH "Notes"
\fBNotes\fR
.sp 2
   To make LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT take effect, use the command badmin
   hrestart all to restart all sbatchds in the cluster.
.sp 2
   If LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT is set, it overrides the setting of the
   parameter LSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE. The parameter
   LSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE is ignored.
.sp 2
   The difference between LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT set to y and
   LSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE set to y is that with LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT,
   only the per-job memory limit enforced by LSF is enabled. The
   per-process memory limit enforced by the OS is disabled. With
   LSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE set to y, both the per-job memory limit
   enforced by LSF and the per-process memory limit enforced by
   the OS are enabled.
.sp 2
   Changing the default Terminate job control action: You can
   define a different Terminate action in lsb.queues with the
   parameter JOB_CONTROLS if you do not want the job to be
   killed. For more details on job controls, see Administering
   Platform LSF.
.sp 2 .SH "Limitations"
\fBLimitations\fR
.sp 2
   If a job is running and the parameter is changed, LSF is not
   able to reset the type of limit enforcement for running jobs.
.sp 2
     o  
         If the parameter is changed from per-process limit
         enforced by the OS to per-job limit enforced by LSF
         (LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT=n or not defined changed to
         LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT=y), both per-process limit and per-job
         limit affect the running job. This means that signals
         may be sent to the job either when the memory allocated
         to an individual process exceeds the memory limit or the
         sum of memory allocated to all processes of the job
         exceed the limit. A job that is running may be killed by
         LSF.
.sp 2
     o  
         If the parameter is changed from per-job limit enforced
         by LSF to per-process limit enforced by the OS
         (LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT=y changed to LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT=n or not
         defined), the job is allowed to run without limits
         because the per-process limit was previously disabled.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE, LSB_MOD_ALL_JOBS, lsb.queues, bsub,
   JOB_TERMINATE_INTERVAL in lsb.params
.sp 2
\fBLSB_JOB_OUTPUT_LOGGING\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_JOB_OUTPUT_LOGGING=Y\fR | \fRN\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Determines whether jobs write job notification messages to the
   logfile.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined (jobs do not write job notification messages to
   the logfile).
.sp 2
\fBLSB_KEEP_SYSDEF_RLIMIT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_KEEP_SYSDEF_RLIMIT=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If resource limits are configured for a user in the SGI IRIX
   User Limits Database (ULDB) domain specified in
   LSF_ULDB_DOMAIN, and there is no domain default, the system
   default is honored.
.sp 2
   If LSB_KEEP_SYSDEF_RLIMIT=n, and no resource limits are
   configured in the domain for the user and there is no domain
   default, LSF overrides the system default and sets system
   limits to unlimited.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. No resource limits are configured in the domain
   for the user and there is no domain default.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_LOAD_TO_SERVER_HOSTS (OBSOLETE)\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_LOAD_TO_SERVER_HOSTS=Y\fR | \fRy\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
      \fBNote: \fR
.sp 2
         This parameter is obsolete in LSF 7 Update 2. By
         default, client sbatchd contacts the local LIM for host
         status and load information.
.sp 2
   Highly recommended for large clusters to decrease the load on
   the master LIM. Forces the client sbatchd to contact the local
   LIM for host status and load information. The client sbatchd
   only contacts the master LIM or a LIM on one of the
   LSF_SERVER_HOSTS if sbatchd cannot find the information
   locally.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Y. Client sbatchd contacts the local LIM for host status and
   load information.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_SERVER_HOSTS in slave.config
.sp 2
\fBLSB_LOCALDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_LOCALDIR=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables duplicate logging.
.sp 2
   Specify the path to a local directory that exists only on the
   first LSF master host. LSF puts the primary copies of the
   event and accounting log files in this directory. LSF puts the
   duplicates in \fBLSB_SHAREDIR\fR.
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         Always restart both the mbactchd and sbatchd when
         modifying LSB_LOCALDIR.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_LOCALDIR=/usr/share/lsbatch/loginfo
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_SHAREDIR, EVENT_UPDATE_INTERVAL in lsb.params
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAILPROG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAILPROG=\fR\fIfile_name\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Path and file name of the mail program used by LSF to send
   email. This is the electronic mail program that LSF uses to
   send system messages to the user. When LSF needs to send email
   to users it invokes the program defined by LSB_MAILPROG in
   lsf.conf. You can write your own custom mail program and set
   LSB_MAILPROG to the path where this program is stored.
.sp 2
   LSF administrators can set the parameter as part of cluster
   reconfiguration. Provide the name of any mail program. For
   your convenience, LSF provides the sendmail mail program,
   which supports the sendmail protocol on UNIX.
.sp 2
   In a mixed cluster, you can specify different programs for
   Windows and UNIX. You can set this parameter during
   installation on Windows. For your convenience, LSF provides
   the lsmail.exe mail program, which supports SMTP and Microsoft
   Exchange Server protocols on Windows. If lsmail is specified,
   the parameter LSB_MAILSERVER must also be specified.
.sp 2
   If you change your mail program, the LSF administrator must
   restart sbatchd on all hosts to retrieve the new value.
.sp 2 .SH "UNIX"
\fBUNIX\fR
.sp 2
   By default, LSF uses /usr/lib/sendmail to send email to users.
   LSF calls LSB_MAILPROG with two arguments; one argument gives
   the full name of the sender, and the other argument gives the
   return address for mail.
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILPROG must read the body of the mail message from the
   standard input. The end of the message is marked by
   end-of-file. Any program or shell script that accepts the
   arguments and input, and delivers the mail correctly, can be
   used.
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILPROG must be executable by any user.
.sp 2 .SH "Windows"
\fBWindows\fR
.sp 2
   If LSB_MAILPROG is not defined, no email is sent.
.sp 2 .SH "Examples"
\fBExamples\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILPROG=lsmail.exe
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILPROG=/serverA/tools/lsf/bin/unixhost.exe 
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   /usr/lib/sendmail (UNIX)
.sp 2
   blank (Windows)
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILSERVER, LSB_MAILTO
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAILSERVER\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAILSERVER=\fR\fImail_protocol\fR\fR:\fR\fImail_server\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Part of mail configuration on Windows.
.sp 2
   This parameter only applies when lsmail is used as the mail
   program (LSB_MAILPROG=lsmail.exe).Otherwise, it is ignored.
.sp 2
   Both \fImail_protocol\fR and \fImail_server\fR must be
   indicated.
.sp 2
   Set this parameter to either SMTP or Microsoft Exchange
   protocol (SMTP or EXCHANGE) and specify the name of the host
   that is the mail server.
.sp 2
   This parameter is set during installation of LSF on Windows or
   is set or modified by the LSF administrator.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is modified, the LSF administrator must
   restart sbatchd on all hosts to retrieve the new value.
.sp 2 .SH "Examples"
\fBExamples\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILSERVER=EXCHANGE:Host2@company.com
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILSERVER=SMTP:MailHost
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_LOCALDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT=\fR\fIemail_size_KB\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Limits the size in KB of the email containing job output
   information.
.sp 2
   The system sends job information such as CPU, process and
   memory usage, job output, and errors in email to the
   submitting user account. Some batch jobs can create large
   amounts of output. To prevent large job output files from
   interfering with your mail system, use LSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT to
   set the maximum size in KB of the email containing the job
   information. Specify a positive integer.
.sp 2
   If the size of the job output email exceeds
   LSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT, the output is saved to a file under
   JOB_SPOOL_DIR or to the default job output directory if
   JOB_SPOOL_DIR is not defined. The email informs users of where
   the job output is located.
.sp 2
   If the -o option of bsub is used, the size of the job output
   is not checked against LSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT.
.sp 2
   If you use a custom mail program specified by the LSB_MAILPROG
   parameter that can use the LSB_MAILSIZE environment variable,
   it is not necessary to configure LSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   By default, LSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT is not enabled. No limit is set
   on size of batch job output email.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILPROG, LSB_MAILTO
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAIL_FROM_DOMAIN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAIL_FROM_DOMAIN=\fR\fIdomain_name\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Windows only.
.sp 2
   LSF uses the username as the from address to send mail. In
   some environments the from address requires domain
   information. If \fBLSB_MAIL_FROM_DOMAIN\fR is set, the domain
   name specified in this parameter will be added to the from
   address.
.sp 2
   For example, if \fBLSB_MAIL_FROM_DOMAIN\fR is not set the,
   from address is SYSTEM; if
   \fRLSB_MAIL_FROM_DOMAIN=platform.com\fR, the from address is
   SYSTEM@platform.com.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAILTO\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAILTO=\fR\fImail_account\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   LSF sends electronic mail to users when their jobs complete or
   have errors, and to the LSF administrator in the case of
   critical errors in the LSF system. The default is to send mail
   to the user who submitted the job, on the host on which the
   daemon is running; this assumes that your electronic mail
   system forwards messages to a central mailbox.
.sp 2
   The LSB_MAILTO parameter changes the mailing address used by
   LSF. LSB_MAILTO is a format string that is used to build the
   mailing address.
.sp 2
   Common formats are:
.sp 2
     o  
         \fR!U\fR :  Mail is sent to the submitting user's
         account name on the local host. The substring \fR!U\fR,
         if found, is replaced with the user’s account name.
.sp 2
     o  
         \fR!U@company_name.com\fR :  Mail is sent to
         \fRuser@company_name.com\fR on the mail server. The mail
         server is specified by LSB_MAILSERVER.
.sp 2
     o  
         \fR!U@!H\fR :  Mail is sent
         to\fR\fR\fIuser\fR\fR@\fR\fIsubmission_hostname\fR. The
         substring \fR!H\fR is replaced with the name of the
         submission host. This format is valid on UNIX only. It
         is not supported on Windows.
.sp 2
   All other characters (including any other ‘\fR!\fR’) are
   copied exactly.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is modified, the LSF administrator must
   restart sbatchd on all hosts to retrieve the new value.
.sp 2
   Windows only: When a job exception occurs (for example, a job
   is overrun or underrun), an email is sent to the primary
   administrator set in the lsf.cluster.\fIcluster_name\fR file
   to the doman set in LSB_MAILTO. For example, if the primary
   administrator is lsfadmin and LSB_MAILTO=fred@company.com, an
   email is sent to lsfadmin@company.com. The email must be a
   valid Windows email account.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   \fR!U\fR
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MAILPROG, LSB_MAILSIZE_LIMIT
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAX_ASKED_HOSTS_NUMBER\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSB_MAX_ASKED_HOSTS_NUMBER=integer
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Limits the number of hosts a user can specify with the -m
   (host preference) option of the following commands:
.sp 2
     o  
         bsub
.sp 2
     o  
         brun
.sp 2
     o  
         bmod
.sp 2
     o  
         brestart
.sp 2
     o  
         brsvadd
.sp 2
     o  
         brsvmod
.sp 2
     o  
         brsvs
.sp 2
   The job is rejected if more hosts are specified than the value
   of \fBLSB_MAX_ASKED_HOSTS_NUMBER\fR.
.sp 2
      \fBCAUTION: \fR
.sp 2
         If this value is set high, there will be a performance
         effect if users submit or modify jobs using the -m
         option and specify a large number of hosts. 512 hosts is
         the suggested upper limit.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Any whole, positive integer.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   512
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAX_JOB_DISPATCH_PER_SESSION \fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAX_JOB_DISPATCH_PER_SESSION=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Defines the maximum number of jobs that mbatchd can dispatch
   during one job scheduling session.
.sp 2
   Both mbatchd and sbatchd must be restarted when you change the
   value of this parameter.
.sp 2
   If set to a value greater than 300, the file descriptor limit
   is increased on operating systems that support a file
   descriptor limit greater than 1024.
.sp 2
   Use together with MAX_SBD_CONNS in lsb.params. Set
   LSB_MAX_JOB_DISPATCH_PER_SESSION to a value no greater than
   one-half the value of MAX_SBD_CONNS. This setting configures
   mbatchd to dispatch jobs at a high rate while maintaining the
   processing speed of other mbatchd tasks.
.sp 2 .SH "Examples"
\fBExamples\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAX_JOB_DISPATCH_PER_SESSION=300\fR
.sp 2
   The file descriptor limit is 1024.
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAX_JOB_DISPATCH_PER_SESSION=1000\fR
.sp 2
   The file descriptor limit is greater than 1024 on operating
   systems that support a greater limit.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   300
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   MAX_SBD_CONNS in lsb.params
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAX_PROBE_SBD\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAX_PROBE_SBD=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the maximum number of sbatchd instances can be
   polled by mbatchd in the interval MBD_SLEEP_TIME/10 (6 seconds
   by default). Use this parameter in large clusters to reduce
   the time it takes for mbatchd to probe all sbatchds.
.sp 2
   The value of LSB_MAX_PROBE_SBD cannot be greater than the
   number of hosts in the cluster. If it is, mbatchd adjusts the
   value of LSB_MAX_PROBE_SBD to be same as the number of hosts.
.sp 2
   After modifying LSB_MAX_PROBE_SBD, use badmin mbdrestart to
   restart mbatchd and let the modified value take effect.
.sp 2
   If LSB_MAX_PROBE_SBD is defined, the value of MAX_SBD_FAIL in
   lsb.params can be less than 3.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Any positive integer between 0 and 64
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   20
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   MAX_SBD_FAIL in lsb.params
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MAX_NQS_QUEUES\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MAX_NQS_QUEUES=\fR\fInqs_queues\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The maximum number of NQS queues allowed in the LSF cluster.
   Required for LSF to work with NQS. You must restart mbatchd if
   you change the value of LSB_MAX_NQS_QUEUES.
.sp 2
   The total number of NQS queues configured by NQS_QUEUES in
   lsb.queues cannot exceed the value of LSB_MAX_NQS_QUEUES. NQS
   queues in excess of the maximum queues are ignored.
.sp 2
   If you do not define LSB_MAX_NQS_QUEUES or define an incorrect
   value, LSF-NQS interoperation is disabled.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Any positive integer
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   None
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MBD_BUSY_MSG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MBD_BUSY_MSG="\fR\fImessage_string\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the message displayed when mbatchd is too busy to
   accept new connections or respond to client requests.
.sp 2
   Define this parameter if you want to customize the message.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   String, either non-empty or empty.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. By default, LSF displays the message \fR"LSF is
   processing your request. Please wait..."\fR
.sp 2
   Batch commands retry the connection to mbatchd at the
   intervals specified by the parameters LSB_API_CONNTIMEOUT and
   LSB_API_RECVTIMEOUT.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MBD_CONNECT_FAIL_MSG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MBD_CONNECT_FAIL_MSG="\fR\fImessage_string\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the message displayed when internal system
   connections to mbatchd fail.
.sp 2
   Define this parameter if you want to customize the message.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   String, either non-empty or empty.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. By default, LSF displays the message \fR"Cannot
   connect to LSF. Please wait..."\fR
.sp 2
   Batch commands retry the connection to mbatchd at the
   intervals specified by the parameters LSB_API_CONNTIMEOUT and
   LSB_API_RECVTIMEOUT.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MBD_DOWN_MSG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MBD_DOWN_MSG="\fR\fImessage_string\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the message displayed by the bhosts command when
   mbatchd is down or there is no process listening at either the
   LSB_MBD_PORT or the LSB_QUERY_PORT.
.sp 2
   Define this parameter if you want to customize the message.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   String, either non-empty or empty.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. By default, LSF displays the message \fR"LSF is
   down. Please wait..."\fR
.sp 2
   Batch commands retry the connection to mbatchd at the
   intervals specified by the parameters LSB_API_CONNTIMEOUT and
   LSB_API_RECVTIMEOUT.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MBD_MAX_SIG_COUNT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MBD_MAX_SIG_COUNT=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When a host enters an unknown state, the mbatchd attempts to
   retry any pending jobs. This parameter specifies the maximum
   number of pending signals that the \fRmbatchd\fR deals with
   concurrently in order not to overload it. A high value for
   \fBLSB_MBD_MAX_SIG_COUNT\fR can negatively impact the
   performance of your cluster.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid Valid values"
\fBValid Valid values\fR
.sp 2
   Integers between 5-100, inclusive.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   5
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MBD_PORT \fR
.sp 2
   See LSF_LIM_PORT, LSF_RES_PORT, LSB_MBD_PORT, LSB_SBD_PORT.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MC_CHKPNT_RERUN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MC_CHKPNT_RERUN=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   For checkpointable MultiCluster jobs, if a restart attempt
   fails, the job is rerun from the beginning (instead of from
   the last checkpoint) without administrator or user
   intervention.
.sp 2
   The submission cluster does not need to forward the job again.
   The execution cluster reports the job’s new pending status
   back to the submission cluster, and the job is dispatched to
   the same host to restart from the beginning
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   \fRn\fR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MC_INITFAIL_MAIL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MC_INITFAIL_MAIL=Y\fR | \fRAll\fR | \fRAdministrator\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   MultiCluster job forwarding model only.
.sp 2
   Specify Y to make LSF email the job owner when a job is
   suspended after reaching the retry threshold.
.sp 2
   Specify \fRAdministrator\fR to make LSF email the primary
   administrator when a job is suspended after reaching the retry
   threshold.
.sp 2
   Specify All to make LSF email both the job owner and the
   primary administrator when a job is suspended after reaching
   the retry threshold.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MC_INITFAIL_RETRY\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MC_INITFAIL_RETRY=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   MultiCluster job forwarding model only. Defines the retry
   threshold and causes LSF to suspend a job that repeatedly
   fails to start. For example, specify 2 retry attempts to make
   LSF attempt to start a job 3 times before suspending it.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   5
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MEMLIMIT_ENFORCE=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specify y to enable LSF memory limit enforcement.
.sp 2
   If enabled, LSF sends a signal to kill all processes that
   exceed queue-level memory limits set by MEMLIMIT in lsb.queues
   or job-level memory limits specified by bsub -M
   \fImem_limit\fR.
.sp 2
   Otherwise, LSF passes memory limit enforcement to the OS. UNIX
   operating systems that support RLIMIT_RSS for setrlimit() can
   apply the memory limit to each process.
.sp 2
   The following operating systems do not support memory limit at
   the OS level:
.sp 2
     o  
         Windows
.sp 2
     o  
         Sun Solaris 2.x
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF passes memory limit enforcement to the OS.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   lsb.queues
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MIG2PEND\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MIG2PEND=0\fR | \fR1\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Applies only to migrating checkpointable or rerunnable jobs.
.sp 2
   When defined with a value of 1, requeues migrating jobs
   instead of restarting or rerunning them on the first available
   host. Requeues the jobs in the PEND state in order of the
   original submission time and with the original job priority.
.sp 2
   If you want to place the migrated jobs at the bottom of the
   queue without considering submission time, define both
   \fBLSB_MIG2PEND\fR=1 and \fBLSB_REQUEUE_TO_BOTTOM\fR=1 in
   lsf.conf.
.sp 2
   Ignored in a MultiCluster environment.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF restarts or reruns migrating jobs on the
   first available host.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_REQUEUE_TO_BOTTOM
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_DELIMITER\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MIXED_PATH_DELIMITER=\fR"\fR|\fR"
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Defines the delimiter between UNIX and Windows paths if
   \fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_ENABLE=y\fR. For example,
   /home/tmp/J.out|c:\\tmp\\J.out.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   A pipe "|" is the default delimiter.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   \fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_ENABLE\fR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_ENABLE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MIXED_PATH_ENABLE=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Allows you to specify both a UNIX and Windows path when
   submitting a job in a mixed cluster (both Windows and UNIX
   hosts).
.sp 2
   The format is always \fRunix_path_cmd|windows_path_cmd\fR.
.sp 2
   Applies to the following options of bsub:
.sp 2
     o  
         -o, -oo
.sp 2
     o  
         -e, -eo
.sp 2
     o  
         -i, -is
.sp 2
     o  
         -cwd
.sp 2
     o  
         -E, -Ep
.sp 2
     o  
         CMD
.sp 2
     o  
         queue level PRE_EXEC, POST_EXEC
.sp 2
     o  
         application level PRE_EXEC, POST_EXEC
.sp 2
   For example:
.sp 2
   bsub -o "/home/tmp/job%J.out|c:\\tmp\\job%J.out" -e
   "/home/tmp/err%J.out|c:\\tmp\\err%J.out" -E "sleep 9| sleep 8"
   -Ep "sleep 7| sleep 6" -cwd "/home/tmp|c:\\tmp" "sleep
   121|sleep 122"
.sp 2
   The delimiter is configurable: \fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_DELIMITER\fR.
.sp 2
      \fBNote: \fR
.sp 2
         \fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_ENABLE\fR doesn't support interactive
         mode (bsub -I).
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF jobs submitted .
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   \fBLSB_MIXED_PATH_DELIMITER\fR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_MOD_ALL_JOBS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_MOD_ALL_JOBS=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, enables bmod to modify resource limits and location of
   job output files for running jobs.
.sp 2
   After a job has been dispatched, the following modifications
   can be made:
.sp 2
     o  
         CPU limit (-c [\fIhour\fR:]\fIminute\fR[/\fIhost_name\fR
         | /\fIhost_model\fR] | -cn)
.sp 2
     o  
         Memory limit (-M \fImem_limit\fR | -Mn)
.sp 2
     o  
         Rerunnable jobs (-r | -rn)
.sp 2
     o  
         Resource requirements (-R "\fIres_req\fR" except -R
         "cu[\fIcu_string\fR]")
.sp 2
     o  
         Run limit (-W \fIrun_limit\fR[/\fIhost_name\fR |
         /\fIhost_model\fR] | -Wn)
.sp 2
     o  
         Standard output file name (-o \fIoutput_file\fR | -on)
.sp 2
     o  
         Standard error file name (-e \fIerror_file\fR | -en)
.sp 2
     o  
         Overwrite standard output (stdout) file name up to 4094
         characters for UNIX or 255 characters for Windows (-oo
         \fIoutput_file\fR)
.sp 2
     o  
         Overwrite standard error (stderr) file name up to 4094
         characters for UNIX or 255 characters for Windows (-eo
         \fIerror_file\fR)
.sp 2
   To modify the CPU limit or the memory limit of running jobs,
   the parameters LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT=Y and LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT=Y must
   be defined in lsf.conf.
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         Always run badmin mbdrestart after modifying
         LSB_MOD_ALL_JOBS.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_JOB_CPULIMIT, LSB_JOB_MEMLIMIT
.sp 2
\fBLSB_NCPU_ENFORCE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When set to 1, enables parallel fairshare and considers the
   number of CPUs when calculating dynamic priority for
   queue-level user-based fairshare. LSB_NCPU_ENFORCE does not
   apply to host-partition user-based fairshare. For
   host-partition user-based fairshare, the number of CPUs is
   automatically considered.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_NQS_PORT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_NQS_PORT=\fR\fIport_number\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Required for LSF to work with NQS.
.sp 2
   TCP service port to use for communication with NQS.
.sp 2 .SH "Where defined"
\fBWhere defined\fR
.sp 2
   This parameter can alternatively be set as an environment
   variable or in the services database such as /etc/services.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_NQS_PORT=607\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_NUM_NIOS_CALLBACK_THREADS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_NUM_NIOS_CALLBACK_THREADS=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the number of callback threads to use for batch
   queries.
.sp 2
   If your cluster runs a large amount of blocking mode (bsub -K)
   and interactive jobs (bsub -I), response to batch queries can
   become very slow. If you run large number of bsub -I or bsub
   -K jobs, you can define the threads to the number of
   processors on the master host.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_PSET_BIND_DEFAULT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_PSET_BIND_DEFAULT=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, Platform LSF HPC binds a job that is not explicitly
   associated with an HP-UX pset to the default pset 0. If
   LSB_PSET_BIND_DEFAULT is not set, LSF HPC must still attach
   the job to a pset, and so binds the job to the same pset used
   by the LSF HPC daemons.
.sp 2
   Use LSB_PSET_BIND_DEFAULT to improve LSF daemon performance by
   automatically unbinding a job with no pset options from the
   pset used by the LSF daemons, and binding it to the default
   pset.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_QUERY_PORT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_QUERY_PORT=\fR\fIport_number\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Optional. Applies only to UNIX platforms that support thread
   programming.
.sp 2
   When using MultiCluster, \fBLSB_QUERY_PORT\fR must be defined
   on all clusters.
.sp 2
   This parameter is recommended for busy clusters with many jobs
   and frequent query requests to increase mbatchd performance
   when you use the bjobs command.
.sp 2
   This may indirectly increase overall mbatchd performance.
.sp 2
   The port_number is the TCP/IP port number to be used by
   mbatchd to only service query requests from the LSF system.
   mbatchd checks the query port during initialization.
.sp 2
   If LSB_QUERY_PORT \fIis not\fR defined:
.sp 2
     o  
         mbatchd uses the port specified by LSB_MBD_PORT in
         lsf.conf, or, if LSB_MBD_PORT is not defined, looks into
         the system services database for port numbers to
         communicate with other hosts in the cluster.
.sp 2
     o  
         For each query request it receives, mbatchd forks one
         child mbatchd to service the request. Each child mbatchd
         processes one request and then exits.
.sp 2
   If LSB_QUERY_PORT is defined:
.sp 2
     o  
         mbatchd prepares this port for connection.The default
         behavior of mbatchd changes, a child mbatchd is forked,
         and the child mbatchd creates threads to process
         requests.
.sp 2
     o  
         mbatchd responds to requests by forking one child
         mbatchd. As soon as mbatchd has forked a child mbatchd,
         the child mbatchd takes over and listens on the port to
         process more query requests. For each request, the child
         mbatchd creates a thread to process it.
.sp 2
   The interval used by mbatchd for forking new child mbatchds is
   specified by the parameter MBD_REFRESH_TIME in lsb.params.
.sp 2
   The child mbatchd continues to listen to the port number
   specified by LSB_QUERY_PORT and creates threads to service
   requests until the job changes status, a new job is submitted,
   or the time specified in MBD_REFRESH_TIME in lsb.params has
   passed (see MBD_REFRESH_TIME in lsb.params for more details).
   When any of these happens, the parent mbatchd sends a message
   to the child mbatchd to exit.
.sp 2
   LSB_QUERY_PORT must be defined when NEWJOB_REFRESH=Y in
   lsb.params to enable a child mbatchd to get up to date
   information about new jobs from the parent mbatchd.
.sp 2 .SH "Operating system support"
\fBOperating system support\fR
.sp 2
      \fBTip: \fR
.sp 2
         See the Online Support area of the Platform Computing
         Web site at www.platform.com for the latest information
         about operating systems that support multithreaded
         mbatchd.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   MBD_REFRESH_TIME and NEWJOB_REFRESH in lsb.params
.sp 2
\fBLSB_REQUEUE_TO_BOTTOM\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_REQUEUE_TO_BOTTOM=0\fR | \fR1\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When defined with a value of 1, requeues automatically
   requeued jobs to the bottom of the queue instead of to the
   top. Also requeues migrating jobs to the bottom of the queue
   if \fBLSB_MIG2PEND\fR is also defined with a value of 1.
.sp 2
   Ignored in a MultiCluster environment.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF requeues jobs in order of original submission
   time and job priority.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_MIG2PEND, REQUEUE_EXIT_VALUES in lsb.queues
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RLA_HOST_LIST\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RLA_HOST_LIST="\fR\fIhost_name\fR ...\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   By default, the LSF scheduler can contact the LSF HPC topology
   adapter (RLA) running on any host for Linux/QsNet RMS
   allocation requests. LSB_RLA_HOST_LIST defines a list of hosts
   to restrict which RLAs the LSF scheduler contacts.
.sp 2
   If LSB_RLA_HOST_LIST is configured, you must list at least one
   host per RMS partition for the RMS partition to be considered
   for job scheduling.
.sp 2
   Listed hosts must be defined in
   lsf.cluster.\fIcluster_name\fR.
.sp 2
   Host names are separated by spaces.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RLA_PORT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RLA_PORT=\fR\fIport_number\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   TCP port used for communication between the LSF HPC topology
   adapter (RLA) and the LSF HPC scheduler plugin.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   6883
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RLA_UPDATE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RLA_UPDATE=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies how often the LSF HPC scheduler refreshes free node
   information from the LSF HPC topology adapter (RLA).
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   600 seconds
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RLA_WORKDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RLA_WORKDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Directory to store the LSF HPC topology adapter (RLA) status
   file. Allows RLA to recover its original state when it
   restarts. When RLA first starts, it creates the directory
   defined by LSB_RLA_WORKDIR if it does not exist, then creates
   subdirectories for each host.
.sp 2
   You should avoid using /tmp or any other directory that is
   automatically cleaned up by the system. Unless your
   installation has restrictions on the LSB_SHAREDIR directory,
   you should use the default for LSB_RLA_WORKDIR.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_SHAREDIR/\fIcluster_name\fR/rla_workdir
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RMSACCT_DELAY\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RMSACCT_DELAY=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, RES waits the specified number of seconds before
   exiting to allow LSF and RMS job statistics to synchronize.
.sp 2
   If LSB_RMSACCT_DELAY=0, RES waits forever until the database
   is up to date.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. RES does not wait at all.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RMS_MAXNUMNODES\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RMS_MAXNUMNODES=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Maximum number of nodes in a system. Specifies a maximum value
   for the nodes argument to the topology scheduler options
   specified in:
.sp 2
     o  
         -extsched option of bsub
.sp 2
     o  
         DEFAULT_EXTSCHED and MANDATORY_EXTSCHED in lsb.queues
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   1024
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RMS_MAXNUMRAILS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RMS_MAXNUMRAILS=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Maximum number of rails in a system. Specifies a maximum value
   for the rails argument to the topology scheduler options
   specified in:
.sp 2
     o  
         -extsched option of bsub
.sp 2
     o  
         DEFAULT_EXTSCHED and MANDATORY_EXTSCHED in lsb.queues
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   32
.sp 2
\fBLSB_RMS_MAXPTILE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_RMS_MAXPTILE=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Maximum number of CPUs per node in a system. Specifies a
   maximum value for the ptile argument to the topology scheduler
   options specified in:
.sp 2
     o  
         -extsched option of bsub
.sp 2
     o  
         DEFAULT_EXTSCHED and MANDATORY_EXTSCHED in lsb.queues
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   32
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SLURM_BESTFIT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SLURM_BESTFIT=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables best-fit node allocation for SLURM jobs.
.sp 2
   By default, LSF applies a \fIfirst-fit\fR allocation policy to
   select from the nodes available for the job. The allocations
   are made left to right for all parallel jobs, and right to
   left for all serial jobs (all other job requirements being
   equal).
.sp 2
   In a heterogeneous SLURM cluster, a \fIbest-fit\fR allocation
   may be preferable for clusters where a mix of serial and
   parallel jobs run. In this context, best fit means: "the nodes
   that minimally satisfy the requirements." Nodes with the
   maximum number of CPUs are chosen first. For parallel and
   serial jobs, the nodes with minimal memory, minimal tmp space,
   and minimal weight are chosen.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SBD_PORT\fR
.sp 2
   See LSF_LIM_PORT, LSF_RES_PORT, LSB_MBD_PORT, LSB_SBD_PORT.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SET_TMPDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SET_TMPDIR=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2
   If y, LSF sets the TMPDIR environment variable, overwriting
   the current value with /tmp/\fIjob_ID\fR.tmpdir.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   n
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SHAREDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SHAREDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Directory in which the job history and accounting logs are
   kept for each cluster. These files are necessary for correct
   operation of the system. Like the organization under
   LSB_CONFDIR, there is one subdirectory for each cluster.
.sp 2
   The LSB_SHAREDIR directory must be owned by the LSF
   administrator. It must be accessible from all hosts that can
   potentially become the master host, and must allow read and
   write access from the master host.
.sp 2
   The LSB_SHAREDIR directory typically resides on a reliable
   file server.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_INDEP/work
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_LOCALDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SHORT_HOSTLIST\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SHORT_HOSTLIST=1\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Displays an abbreviated list of hosts in bjobs and bhist for a
   parallel job where multiple processes of a job are running on
   a host. Multiple processes are displayed in the following
   format:
.sp 2
   processes*hostA
.sp 2
   For example, if a parallel job is running 5 processes on
   \fRhostA\fR, the information is displayed in the following
   manner:
.sp 2
   5*hostA
.sp 2
   Setting this parameter may improve mbatchd restart performance
   and accelerate event replay.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SIGSTOP\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SIGSTOP=\fR\fIsignal_name\fR | \fIsignal_value\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the signal sent by the SUSPEND action in LSF. You
   can specify a signal name or a number.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is not defined, by default the SUSPEND
   action in LSF sends the following signals to a job:
.sp 2
     o  
         Parallel or interactive jobs: SIGTSTP is sent to allow
         user programs to catch the signal and clean up. The
         parallel job launcher also catches the signal and stops
         the entire job (task by task for parallel jobs). Once
         LSF sends SIGTSTP, LSF assumes the job is stopped.
.sp 2
     o  
         Other jobs: SIGSTOP is sent. SIGSTOP cannot be caught by
         user programs. The same set of signals is not supported
         on all UNIX systems. To display a list of the symbolic
         names of the signals (without the SIG prefix) supported
         on your system, use the kill -l command.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_SIGSTOP=SIGKILL
.sp 2
   In this example, the SUSPEND action sends the three default
   signals sent by the TERMINATE action (SIGINT, SIGTERM, and
   SIGKILL) 10 seconds apart.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. Default SUSPEND action in LSF is sent.
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SSH_XFORWARD_CMD\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SSH_XFORWARD_CMD\fR=\fI[/path[/path]]ssh command [ssh
   options]\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Optional when submitting jobs with SSH X11 forwarding. Allows
   you to specify an SSH command and options when a job is
   submitted with -XF.
.sp 2
   Replace the default value with an SSH command (full PATH and
   options allowed).
.sp 2
   When running a job with the -XF option, runs the SSH command
   specified here.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   \fRssh -X -n\fR
.sp 2
\fBLSB_STDOUT_DIRECT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_STDOUT_DIRECT=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When set, and used with the -o or -e options of bsub,
   redirects standard output or standard error from the job
   directly to a file as the job runs.
.sp 2
   If LSB_STDOUT_DIRECT is not set and you use the bsub -o
   option, the standard output of a job is written to a temporary
   file and copied to the file you specify \fIafter\fR the job
   finishes.
.sp 2
   LSB_STDOUT_DIRECT is not supported on Windows.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_STOP_IGNORE_IT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Usage"
\fBUsage\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_STOP_IGNORE_IT= Y\fR | \fRy\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Allows a solitary job to be stopped regardless of the idle
   time (IT) of the host that the job is running on. By default,
   if only one job is running on a host, the host idle time must
   be zero in order to stop the job.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSB_SUB_COMMANDNAME\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_SUB_COMMANDNAME=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, enables esub to use the variable LSB_SUB_COMMAND_LINE
   in the esub job parameter file specified by the
   $LSB_SUB_PARM_FILE environment variable.
.sp 2
   The LSB_SUB_COMMAND_LINE variable carries the value of the
   bsub command argument, and is used when esub runs.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   esub contains:
.sp 2
   #!/bin/sh . $LSB_SUB_PARM_FILE exec 1>&2 if [ $LSB_SUB_COMMAND_LINE="netscape" ]; then echo "netscape is not allowed to run in batch mode" exit $LSB_SUB_ABORT_VALUE fi
.sp 2
   LSB_SUB_COMMAND_LINE is defined in $LSB_SUB_PARM_FILE as:
.sp 2
   LSB_SUB_COMMAND_LINE=netscape
.sp 2
   A job submitted with:
.sp 2
   bsub netscape ...
.sp 2
   Causes esub to echo the message:
.sp 2
   netscape is not allowed to run in batch mode
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_SUB_COMMAND_LINE and LSB_SUB_PARM_FILE environment
   variables
.sp 2
\fBLSB_TIME_CMD \fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSB_TIME_CMD=\fR\fItimimg_level\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The timing level for checking how long batch commands run.
