   directories, and examples. For example, defining LSF_INDEP as
   /usr/share/lsf/mnt places man pages in /usr/share/lsf/mnt/man,
   configuration files in /usr/share/lsf/mnt/conf, and so on.
.sp 2
   The files in LSF_INDEP can be shared by all machines in the
   cluster.
.sp 2
   As shown in the following list, LSF_INDEP is incorporated into
   other LSF environment variables.
.sp 2
     o  
         LSB_SHAREDIR=$LSF_INDEP/work
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_CONFDIR=$LSF_INDEP/conf
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_INCLUDEDIR=$LSF_INDEP/include
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_MANDIR=$LSF_INDEP/man
.sp 2
     o  
         XLSF_APPDIR=$LSF_INDEP/misc
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   /usr/share/lsf/mnt
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_MACHDEP, LSB_SHAREDIR, LSF_CONFDIR, LSF_INCLUDEDIR,
   LSF_MANDIR, XLSF_APPDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_INTERACTIVE_STDERR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_INTERACTIVE_STDERR=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Separates \fRstderr\fR from \fRstdout\fR for interactive tasks
   and interactive batch jobs.
.sp 2
   This is useful to redirect output to a file with regular
   operators instead of the bsub -e \fIerr_file\fR and -o
   \fIout_file\fR options.
.sp 2
   This parameter can also be enabled or disabled as an
   environment variable.
.sp 2
      \fBCAUTION: \fR
.sp 2
         If you enable this parameter globally in lsf.conf, check
         any custom scripts that manipulate stderr and stdout.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is not defined or set to n, the following
   are written to \fRstdout\fR on the submission host for
   interactive tasks and interactive batch jobs:
.sp 2
     o  
         Job standard output messages
.sp 2
     o  
         Job standard error messages
.sp 2
   The following are written to \fRstderr\fR on the submission
   host for interactive tasks and interactive batch jobs:
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF messages
.sp 2
     o  
         NIOS standard messages
.sp 2
     o  
         NIOS debug messages (if LSF_NIOS_DEBUG=1 in lsf.conf)
.sp 2
   When this parameter is set to \fRy\fR, the following are
   written to \fRstdout\fR on the submission host for interactive
   tasks and interactive batch jobs:
.sp 2
     o  
         Job standard output messages
.sp 2
   The following are written to \fRstderr\fR on the submission
   host:
.sp 2
     o  
         Job standard error messages
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF messages
.sp 2
     o  
         NIOS standard messages
.sp 2
     o  
         NIOS debug messages (if LSF_NIOS_DEBUG=1 in lsf.conf)
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "Notes"
\fBNotes\fR
.sp 2
   When this parameter is set, the change affects interactive
   tasks and interactive batch jobs run with the following
   commands:
.sp 2
     o  
         bsub -I
.sp 2
     o  
         bsub -Ip
.sp 2
     o  
         bsub -Is
.sp 2
     o  
         lsrun
.sp 2
     o  
         lsgrun
.sp 2
     o  
         lsmake (Platform LSF Make)
.sp 2
     o  
         \fRbsub pam\fR (Platform LSF HPC)
.sp 2 .SH "Limitations"
\fBLimitations\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         Pseudo-terminal: Do not use this parameter if your
         application depends on \fRstderr\fR as a terminal. This
         is because LSF must use a non-pseudo-terminal connection
         to separate \fRstderr\fR from \fRstdout\fR.
.sp 2
     o  
         Synchronization: Do not use this parameter if you depend
         on messages in \fRstderr\fR and \fRstdout\fR to be
         synchronized and jobs in your environment are
         continuously submitted. A continuous stream of messages
         causes \fRstderr\fR and \fRstdout\fR to not be
         synchronized. This can be emphasized with parallel jobs.
         This situation is similar to that of rsh.
.sp 2
     o  
         NIOS standard and debug messages: NIOS standard
         messages, and debug messages (when LSF_NIOS_DEBUG=1 in
         lsf.conf or as an environment variable) are written to
         \fRstderr\fR. NIOS standard messages are in the format
         \fR<<message>>\fR, which makes it easier to remove them
         if you wish. To redirect NIOS debug messages to a file,
         define LSF_CMD_LOGDIR in lsf.conf or as an environment
         variable.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_NIOS_DEBUG, LSF_CMD_LOGDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LD_SECURITY\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LD_SECURITY=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LD_SECURITY: When set, jobs submitted using bsub -Is or
   bsub -Ip cause the environment variables LD_PRELOAD and
   LD_LIBRARY_PATH to be removed from the job environment during
   job initialization to ensure enhanced security against users
   obtaining root privileges.
.sp 2
   Two new environment variables are created (LSF_LD_LIBRARY_PATH
   and LSF_LD_PRELOAD) to allow LD_PRELOAD and LD_LIBRARY_PATH to
   be put back before the job runs.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   N
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIBDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIBDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the directory in which the LSF libraries are
   installed. Library files are shared by all hosts of the same
   type.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_MACHDEP/lib
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIC_SCHED_HOSTS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIC_SCHED_HOSTS="\fR\fIcandidate_host_list\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2
   \fIcandidate_host_list\fR is a space-separated list of hosts
   that are candidate LSF License Scheduler hosts.
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The candidate License Scheduler host list is read by LIM on
   each host to check if the host is a candidate License
   Scheduler master host. If the host is on the list, LIM starts
   the License Scheduler daemon (bld) on the host.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_REQUEUE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_REQUEUE=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Set this parameter to requeue a job whose license is preempted
   by LSF License Scheduler. The job is killed and requeued
   instead of suspended.
.sp 2
   If you set LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_REQUEUE, do not set
   LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE. If both these parameters
   are set, LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE is ignored.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   N
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE, LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_STOP
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Set this parameter to release the slot of a job that is
   suspended when its license is preempted by LSF License
   Scheduler.
.sp 2
   If you set LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE, do not set
   LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_REQUEUE. If both these parameters are
   set, LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE is ignored.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Y
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_REQUEUE, LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_STOP
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_STOP\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_STOP=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Set this parameter to use job controls to stop a job that is
   preempted. When this parameter is set, a UNIX SIGSTOP signal
   is sent to suspend a job instead of a UNIX SIGTSTP.
.sp 2
   To send a SIGSTOP signal instead of SIGTSTP, the following
   parameter in lsb.queues must also be set:
.sp 2
   JOB_CONTROLS=SUSPEND[SIGSTOP]
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   N
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_SLOT_RELEASE,
   LSF_LIC_SCHED_PREEMPT_REQUEUE
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIC_SCHED_STRICT_PROJECT_NAME\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIC_SCHED_STRICT_PROJECT_NAME=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enforces strict checking of the License Scheduler project name
   upon job submission or job modification (bsub or bmod). If the
   project named is misspelled (case sensitivity applies), the
   job is rejected.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is not set or it is set to n, and if there
   is an error in the project name, the default project is used.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   N
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LICENSE_ACCT_PATH\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LICENSE_ACCT_PATH=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the location for the license accounting files. These
   include the license accounting files for LSF Family products.
.sp 2
   Use this parameter to define the location of all the license
   accounting files. By defining this parameter, you can store
   the license accounting files for the LSF Family of products in
   the same directory for convenience.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. The license accounting files are stored in the
   default log directory for the particular product. For example,
   LSF stores its license audit file in the LSF system log file
   directory.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
     o  
         lsf.cluster_name.license.acct
.sp 2
     o  
         bld.license.acct
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LICENSE_FILE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LICENSE_FILE="\fR\fIfile_name \fR... |
   \fIport_number\fR\fR@\fR\fIhost_name\fR[\fR:\fR\fIport_number\fR\fR@\fR\fIhost_name\fR
   ...]\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies one or more demo or FLEXnet permanent license files
   used by LSF.
.sp 2
   The value for LSF_LICENSE_FILE can be either of the following:
.sp 2
     o  
         The full path name to the license file.
.sp 2
           o  
               UNIX example:
.sp 2
               LSF_LICENSE_FILE=/usr/share/lsf/cluster1/conf/license.dat
.sp 2
           o  
               Windows examples:
.sp 2
               \fRLSF_LICENSE_FILE= C:\\licenses\\license.dat\fR
.sp 2
               \fRLSF_LICENSE_FILE=\\\\HostA\\licenses\\license.dat\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         For a permanent license, the name of the license server
         host and TCP port number used by the lmgrd daemon, in
         the format \fIport\fR@\fIhost_name\fR. For example:
.sp 2
         LSF_LICENSE_FILE="1700@hostD"
.sp 2
     o  
         For a license with redundant servers, use a comma to
         separate the \fIport\fR@\fIhost_names\fR. The port
         number must be the same as that specified in the SERVER
         line of the license file. For example:
.sp 2
         UNIX:
.sp 2
         LSF_LICENSE_FILE="port@hostA:port@hostB:port@hostC"
.sp 2
         Windows:
.sp 2
         LSF_LICENSE_FILE="port@hostA;port@hostB;port@hostC"
.sp 2
     o  
         For a license with distributed servers, use a pipe to
         separate the \fIport\fR@\fIhost_names\fR. The port
         number must be the same as that specified in the SERVER
         line of the license file. For example:
.sp 2
         LSF_LICENSE_FILE="port@hostA|port@hostB|port@hostC"
.sp 2
   Multiple license files should be quoted and must be separated
   by a pipe character (|).
.sp 2
   Windows example:
.sp 2
   LSF_LICENSE_FILE="C:\\licenses\\license1|C:\\licenses\\license2|D:\\mydir\\license3"
.sp 2
   Multiple files may be kept in the same directory, but each one
   must reference a different license server. When checking out a
   license, LSF searches the servers in the order in which they
   are listed, so it checks the second server when there are no
   more licenses available from the first server.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is not defined, LSF assumes the default
   location.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   The default licence installation directory is the value of the
   parameter \fBLSF_SERVERDIR\fR in lsf.conf.
.sp 2
   Demo license: The default demo licence installation directory
   is /usr/local/flexlm/.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LICENSE_MAINTENANCE_INTERVAL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LICENSE_MAINTENANCE_INTERVAL=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies how often LSF checks the LSF licences when starting
   or restarting the cluster. A small number could delay LSF.
   Valid values are from 5 to 300.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is not set, the default value is used.
.sp 2 .SH "Recommended value"
\fBRecommended value\fR
.sp 2
   Set LSF_LICENSE_MAINTENANCE_INTERVAL depending on your cluster
   size, system buffer size, license server, and cluster
   communication speed:
.sp 2
     o  
         If you have network delays or a small system buffer
         (less than 32 KB), set LSF_LICENSE_MAINTENANCE to the
         high end of the valid values (300).
.sp 2
     o  
         For a small cluster (fewer than 1000 hosts), specify
         LSF_LICENSE_MAINTENANCE_INTERVAL with 5-60 second value.
.sp 2
     o  
         For a large cluster (greater than 4000 hosts) with
         limited licenses, use the maximum value: 300 seconds.
.sp 2
     o  
         If you have slow cluster communication (for example, if
         you use a Web-based intranet), use the maximum value:
         300 seconds.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   5 seconds
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LICENSE_NOTIFICATION_INTERVAL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LICENSE_MAINTENANCE_INTERVAL=\fR\fItime_hours\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies how often notification email is sent to the primary
   cluster administrator about overuse of LSF Family product
   licenses and LSF License Scheduler tokens.
.sp 2 .SH "Recommended value"
\fBRecommended value\fR
.sp 2
   To avoid getting the same audit information more than once,
   set LSF_LICENSE_NOTIFICATION_INTERVAL greater than 24 hours.
.sp 2 .SH "Example notification email"
\fBExample notification email\fR
.sp 2
   Subject: LSF license overuse LSF Administrator: Your cluster has experienced license overuse. Platform Product License Name: LSF_MANAGER CLASS E license usage: 0 in total; 8 in use (8 overused).  Overuse Hosts:  hostA Use lim -t and lshosts -l or see /usr/opt/lsf7.0/log/lsf.cluster_7.0.license.acct file for details. Please contact Platform Support at support@platform.com for information about getting additional licenses.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   24 hours
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_LICENSE_ACCT_PATH
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
     o  
         lsf.cluster_name.license.acct
.sp 2
     o  
         bld.license.acct
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIM_API_NTRIES\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIM_API_NTRIES=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Defines the number of times LSF commands will try to
   communicate with the LIM API when LIM is not available.
   LSF_LIM_API_NTRIES is ignored by LSF and EGO daemons and EGO
   commands. The LSF_LIM_API_NTRIES environment variable.
   overrides the value of LSF_LIM_API_NTRIES in lsf.conf.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   1 to 65535
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   1. LIM API exits without retrying.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIM_DEBUG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIM_DEBUG=1\fR | \fR2\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Sets LSF to debug mode.
.sp 2
   If LSF_LIM_DEBUG is defined, LIM operates in single user mode.
   No security checking is performed, so LIM should not run as
   root.
.sp 2
   LIM does not look in the services database for the LIM service
   port number. Instead, it uses port number 36000 unless
   LSF_LIM_PORT has been defined.
.sp 2
   Specify 1 for this parameter unless you are testing LSF.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIM_DEBUG=1
.sp 2
   LIM runs in the background with no associated control
   terminal.
.sp 2
   LSF_LIM_DEBUG=2
.sp 2
   LIM runs in the foreground and prints error messages to
   \fRtty\fR.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_LIM_DEBUG
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_RES_DEBUG, LSF_CMD_LOGDIR, LSF_CMD_LOG_MASK, LSF_LOG_MASK,
   LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIM_IGNORE_CHECKSUM\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIM_IGNORE_CHECKSUM=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Configure LSF_LIM_IGNORE_CHECKSUM=Y to ignore warning messages
   logged to lim log files on non-master hosts.
.sp 2
   When LSF_MASTER_LIST is set, lsadmin reconfig only restarts
   master candidate hosts (for example, after adding or removing
   hosts from the cluster). This can cause superfluous warning
   messages like the following to be logged in the lim log files
   for non-master hosts because lim on these hosts are not
   restarted after configuration change:
.sp 2
   Aug 26 13:47:35 2006 9746 4 7.0 xdr_loadvector: Sender <10.225.36.46:9999> has a different configuration
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_MASTER_LIST
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LIM_PORT, LSF_RES_PORT, LSB_MBD_PORT, LSB_SBD_PORT \fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LIM_PORT=\fR\fIport_number\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   TCP service ports to use for communication with the LSF
   daemons.
.sp 2
   If port parameters are not defined, LSF obtains the port
   numbers by looking up the LSF service names in the
   /etc/services file or the NIS (UNIX). If it is not possible to
   modify the services database, you can define these port
   parameters to set the port numbers.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_LIM_PORT
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   On UNIX, the default is to get port numbers from the services
   database.
.sp 2
   On Windows, these parameters are mandatory.
.sp 2
   Default port number values are:
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_LIM_PORT=7869
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_RES_PORT=6878
.sp 2
     o  
         LSB_MBD_PORT=6881
.sp 2
     o  
         LSB_SBD_PORT=6882
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOAD_USER_PROFILE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSF_LOAD_USER_PROFILE=local | roaming
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When running jobs on Windows hosts, you can specify whether a
   user profile should be loaded. Use this parameter if you have
   jobs that need to access user-specific resources associated
   with a user profile.
.sp 2
   Local and roaming user profiles are Windows features. For more
   information about them, check Microsoft documentation.
.sp 2
     o  
         Local: LSF loads the Windows user profile from the local
         execution machine (the host on which the job runs).
.sp 2
            \fBNote: \fR
.sp 2
               If the user has logged onto the machine before,
               the profile of that user is used. If not, the
               profile for the default user is used
.sp 2
     o  
         Roaming: LSF loads a roaming user profile if it has been
         set up. If not, the local user profile is loaded
         instead.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. No user profiles are loaded when jobs run on
   Windows hosts.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES="\fR\fIresource\fR ...\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Defines instances of local resources residing on the slave
   host.
.sp 2
     o  
         For numeric resources, defined name-value pairs:
.sp 2
         "[resourcemap value*resource_name]"
.sp 2
     o  
         For Boolean resources, the value is the resource name in
         the form:
.sp 2
         "[resource resource_name]"
.sp 2
   When the slave host calls the master host to add itself, it
   also reports its local resources. The local resources to be
   added must be defined in lsf.shared.
.sp 2
   If the same resource is already defined in lsf.shared as
   default or all, it cannot be added as a local resource. The
   shared resource overrides the local one.
.sp 2
      \fBTip: \fR
.sp 2
         LSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES is usually set in the slave.config
         file during installation. If LSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES are
         already defined in a local lsf.conf on the slave host,
         lsfinstall \fIdoes not\fR add resources you define in
         LSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES in slave.config. You should not have
         duplicate LSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES entries in lsf.conf. If
         local resources are defined more than once, only the
         last definition is valid.
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         Resources must already be mapped to hosts in the
         ResourceMap section of lsf.cluster.\fIcluster_name\fR.
         If the ResourceMap section does not exist, local
         resources are not added.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LOCAL_RESOURCES="[resourcemap 1*verilog] [resource linux]"
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_LOCAL_RESOURCES
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOG_MASK\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LOG_MASK=\fR\fImessage_log_level\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the logging level of error messages for LSF daemons,
   except LIM, which is controlled by Platform EGO.
.sp 2
   For example:
.sp 2
   LSF_LOG_MASK=LOG_DEBUG
.sp 2
   If EGO is enabled in the LSF cluster, and EGO_LOG_MASK is not
   defined, LSF uses the value of LSF_LOG_MASK for LIM, PIM, and
   MELIM. EGO vemkd and pem components continue to use the EGO
   default values. If EGO_LOG_MASK is defined, and EGO is
   enabled, then EGO value is taken.
.sp 2
   To specify the logging level of error messages for LSF
   commands, use LSF_CMD_LOG_MASK. To specify the logging level
   of error messages for LSF batch commands, use
   LSB_CMD_LOG_MASK.
.sp 2
   On UNIX, this is similar to syslog. All messages logged at the
   specified level or higher are recorded; lower level messages
   are discarded. The LSF_LOG_MASK value can be any log priority
   symbol that is defined in syslog.h (see syslog).
.sp 2
   The log levels in order from highest to lowest are:
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_EMERG
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_ALERT
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_CRIT
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_ERR
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_WARNING
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_NOTICE
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_INFO
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_DEBUG
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_DEBUG1
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_DEBUG2
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_DEBUG3
.sp 2
   The most important LSF log messages are at the LOG_ERR or
   LOG_WARNING level. Messages at the LOG_INFO and LOG_DEBUG
   level are only useful for debugging.
.sp 2
   Although message log level implements similar functionality to
   UNIX syslog, there is no dependency on UNIX syslog. It works
   even if messages are being logged to files instead of syslog.
.sp 2
   LSF logs error messages in different levels so that you can
   choose to log all messages, or only log messages that are
   deemed critical. The level specified by LSF_LOG_MASK
   determines which messages are recorded and which are
   discarded. All messages logged at the specified level or
   higher are recorded, while lower level messages are discarded.
.sp 2
   For debugging purposes, the level LOG_DEBUG contains the
   fewest number of debugging messages and is used for basic
   debugging. The level LOG_DEBUG3 records all debugging
   messages, and can cause log files to grow very large; it is
   not often used. Most debugging is done at the level
   LOG_DEBUG2.
.sp 2
   In versions earlier than LSF 4.0, you needed to restart the
   daemons after setting LSF_LOG_MASK in order for your changes
   to take effect.
.sp 2
   LSF 4.0 implements dynamic debugging, which means you do not
   need to restart the daemons after setting a debugging
   environment variable.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_LOG_MASK
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LOG_WARNING
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_CMD_LOG_MASK, LSB_CMD_LOGDIR, LSB_DEBUG, LSB_DEBUG_CMD,
   LSB_DEBUG_NQS, LSB_TIME_CMD, LSF_CMD_LOGDIR, LSF_CMD_LOG_MASK,
   LSF_DEBUG_LIM, LSB_DEBUG_MBD, LSF_DEBUG_RES, LSB_DEBUG_SBD,
   LSB_DEBUG_SCH, LSF_LOG_MASK, LSF_LOGDIR, LSF_TIME_CMD
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOG_MASK_WIN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LOG_MASK_WIN=\fR\fImessage_log_level\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Allows you to reduce the information logged to the LSF Windows
   event log files. Messages of lower severity than the specified
   level are discarded.
.sp 2
   For all LSF files, the types of messages saved depends on
   LSF_LOG_MASK, so the threshold for the Windows event logs is
   either LSF_LOG_MASK or LSF_LOG_MASK_WIN, whichever is higher.
   LSF_LOG_MASK_WIN is ignored if LSF_LOG_MASK is set to a higher
   level.
.sp 2
   The LSF event log files for Windows are:
.sp 2
     o  
         lim.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         res.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         sbatchd.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         mbatchd.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         pim.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
   The log levels you can specify for this parameter, in order
   from highest to lowest, are:
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_ERR
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_WARNING
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_INFO
.sp 2
     o  
         LOG_NONE (LSF does not log Windows events)
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LOG_ERR
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LOG_MASK
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOGDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LOGDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Defines the LSF system log file directory. Error messages from
   all servers are logged into files in this directory. To
   effectively use debugging, set LSF_LOGDIR to a directory such
   as /tmp. This can be done in your own environment from the
   shell or in lsf.conf.
.sp 2 .SH "Windows"
\fBWindows\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LOGDIR is required on Windows if you wish to enable
   logging.
.sp 2
   You must also define LSF_LOGDIR_USE_WIN_REG=n.
.sp 2
   If you define LSF_LOGDIR without defining
   LSF_LOGDIR_USE_WIN_REG=n, LSF logs error messages into files
   in the default local directory specified in one of the
   following Windows registry keys:
.sp 2
     o  
         On Windows 2000, Windows XP, and Windows 2003:
.sp 2
         HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SOFTWARE\\Platform Computing Corporation\\LSF\\cluster_name\\LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
     o  
         On Windows XP x64 and Windows 2003 x64:
.sp 2
         HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SOFTWARE\\Wow6432Node\\Platform Computing Corporation\\LSF\\cluster_name\\LSF_LOGDIR 
.sp 2
   If a server is unable to write in the LSF system log file
   directory, LSF attempts to write to the following directories
   in the following order:
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_TMPDIR if defined
.sp 2
     o  
         \fR%TMP%\fR if defined
.sp 2
     o  
         \fR%TEMP%\fR if defined
.sp 2
     o  
         System directory, for example, c:\\winnt
.sp 2 .SH "UNIX"
\fBUNIX\fR
.sp 2
   If a server is unable to write in this directory, the error
   logs are created in /tmp on UNIX.
.sp 2
   If LSF_LOGDIR is not defined, syslog is used to log everything
   to the system log using the LOG_DAEMON facility. The syslog
   facility is available by default on most UNIX systems. The
   /etc/syslog.conf file controls the way messages are logged and
   the files they are logged to. See the man pages for the
   syslogd daemon and the syslog function for more information.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. On UNIX, log messages go to syslog. On Windows,
   no logging is performed.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_CMD_LOG_MASK, LSB_CMD_LOGDIR, LSB_DEBUG, LSB_DEBUG_CMD,
   LSB_TIME_CMD, LSF_CMD_LOGDIR, LSF_CMD_LOG_MASK, LSF_LOG_MASK,
   LSF_LOGDIR_USE_WIN_REG, LSF_TIME_CMD
.sp 2 .SH "Files"
\fBFiles\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         lim.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         res.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         sbatchd.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         \fRsbatchdc.log.host_name\fR\fI\fR(when
         LSF_DAEMON_WRAP=Y)
.sp 2
     o  
         mbatchd.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         eeventd.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         pim.log.\fIhost_name\fR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOGDIR_USE_WIN_REG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LOGDIR_USE_WIN_REG=n\fR | \fRN\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Windows only.
.sp 2
   If set, LSF logs error messages into files in the directory
   specified by LSF_LOGDIR in lsf.conf.
.sp 2
   Use this parameter to enable LSF to save log files in a
   different location from the default local directory specified
   in the Windows registry.
.sp 2
   If not set, or if set to any value other than N or n, LSF logs
   error messages into files in the default local directory
   specified in one of the following Windows registry keys:
.sp 2
     o  
         On Windows 2000, Windows XP, and Windows 2003:
.sp 2
         HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SOFTWARE\\Platform Computing Corporation\\LSF\\cluster_name\\LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
     o  
         On Windows XP x64 and Windows 2003 x64:
.sp 2
         HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SOFTWARE\\Wow6432Node\\Platform Computing Corporation\\LSF\\cluster_name\\LSF_LOGDIR 
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not set.
.sp 2
   LSF uses the default local directory specified in the Windows
   registry.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LOGFILE_OWNER\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LOGFILE_OWNER="\fR\fIuser_name\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies an owner for the LSF log files other than the
   default, the owner of lsf.conf. To specify a Windows user
   account, include the domain name in uppercase letters
   (\fIDOMAIN_NAME\fR\\\fIuser_name\fR).
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not set. The LSF Administrator with root privileges is the
   owner of LSF log files.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_LSLOGIN_SSH\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_LSLOGIN_SSH=YES\fR | \fRyes\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables SSH to secure communication between hosts and during
   job submission.
.sp 2
   SSH is used when running any of the following:
.sp 2
     o  
         Remote log on to a lightly loaded host (lslogin)
.sp 2
     o  
         An interactive job (bsub -IS | -ISp | ISs)
.sp 2
     o  
         An X-window job (bsub -IX)
.sp 2
     o  
         An externally submitted job that is interactive or
         X-window (esub)
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not set. LSF uses \fBrlogin\fR to authenticate users.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MACHDEP\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MACHDEP=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the directory in which machine-dependent files are
   installed. These files cannot be shared across different types
   of machines.
.sp 2
   In clusters with a single host type, LSF_MACHDEP is usually
   the same as LSF_INDEP. The machine dependent files are the
   user commands, daemons, and libraries. You should not need to
   modify this parameter.
.sp 2
   As shown in the following list, LSF_MACHDEP is incorporated
   into other LSF variables.
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_BINDIR=$LSF_MACHDEP/bin
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_LIBDIR=$LSF_MACHDEP/lib
.sp 2
     o  
         LSF_SERVERDIR=$LSF_MACHDEP/etc
.sp 2
     o  
         XLSF_UIDDIR=$LSF_MACHDEP/lib/uid
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   /usr/share/lsf
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_INDEP
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MANDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MANDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Directory under which all man pages are installed.
.sp 2
   The man pages are placed in the man1, man3, man5, and man8
   subdirectories of the LSF_MANDIR directory. This is created by
   the LSF installation process, and you should not need to
   modify this parameter.
.sp 2
   Man pages are installed in a format suitable for BSD-style man
   commands.
.sp 2
   For most versions of UNIX and Linux, you should add the
   directory LSF_MANDIR to your MANPATH environment variable. If
   your system has a man command that does not understand
   MANPATH, you should either install the man pages in the
   /usr/man directory or get one of the freely available man
   programs.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_INDEP/man
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MASTER_LIST\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MASTER_LIST="\fR\fIhost_name ...\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Required. Defines a list of hosts that are candidates to
   become the master host for the cluster.
.sp 2
   Listed hosts must be defined in
   lsf.cluster.\fIcluster_name\fR.
.sp 2
   Host names are separated by spaces.
.sp 2
      \fBTip: \fR
.sp 2
         On UNIX and Linux, master host candidates should share
         LSF configuration and binaries. On Windows,
         configuration files are shared, but not binaries.
.sp 2
   Starting in LSF 7, LSF_MASTER_LIST \fImust\fR be defined in
   lsf.conf.
.sp 2
   If EGO is enabled, LSF_MASTER_LIST can only be defined
   lsf.conf. EGO_MASTER_LIST can only be defined in ego.conf.
   EGO_MASTER_LIST cannot be defined in lsf.conf. LSF_MASTER_LIST
   cannot be defined ego.conf.
.sp 2
   LIM reads EGO_MASTER_LIST wherever it is defined. If both
   LSF_MASTER_LIST and EGO_MASTER_LIST are defined, the value of
   EGO_MASTER_LIST in ego.conf is taken. To avoid errors, you
   should make sure that the value of LSF_MASTER_LIST matches the
   value of EGO_MASTER_LIST, or define only EGO_MASTER_LIST.
.sp 2
   If EGO is disabled, ego.conf not loaded and the value of
   LSF_MASTER_LIST defined in lsf.conf is taken.
.sp 2
   When you run lsadmin reconfig to reconfigure the cluster, only
   the master LIM candidates read lsf.shared and
   lsf.cluster.\fIcluster_name\fR to get updated information. The
   elected master LIM sends configuration information to slave
   LIMs.
.sp 2
   If you have a large number of non-master hosts, you should
   configure LSF_LIM_IGNORE_CHECKSUM=Y to ignore warning messages
   like the following logged to lim log files on non-master
   hosts.
.sp 2
   Aug 26 13:47:35 2006 9746 4 7.0 xdr_loadvector: Sender <10.225.36.46:9999> has a different configuration
.sp 2 .SH "Interaction with LSF_SERVER_HOSTS"
\fBInteraction with LSF_SERVER_HOSTS\fR
.sp 2
   You can use the same list of hosts, or a subset of the master
   host list defined in LSF_MASTER_LIST, in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS. If
   you include the primary master host in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS, you
   should define it as the last host of the list.
.sp 2
   If LSF_ADD_CLIENTS is defined in install.config at
   installation, lsfinstall automatically appends the hosts in
   LSF_MASTER_LIST to the list of hosts in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS so
   that the primary master host is last. For example:
.sp 2
   LSF_MASTER_LIST="lsfmaster hostE"
.sp 2
   LSF_SERVER_HOSTS="hostB hostC hostD hostE lsfmaster"
.sp 2
   The value of LSF_SERVER_HOSTS is not changed during upgrade.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_MASTER_LIST
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Defined at installation
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIM_IGNORE_CHECKSUM
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MASTER_NSLOOKUP_TIMEOUT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MASTER_NSLOOKUP_TIMEOUT=\fR\fItime_milliseconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Timeout in milliseconds that the master LIM waits for DNS host
   name lookup.
.sp 2
   If LIM spends a lot of time calling DNS to look up a host
   name, LIM appears to hang.
.sp 2
   This parameter is used by master LIM only. Only the master LIM
   detects this parameter and enable the DNS lookup timeout.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. No timeout for DNS lookup
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIM_IGNORE_CHECKSUM
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MAX_TRY_ADD_HOST\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MAX_TRY_ADD_HOST=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When a slave LIM on a dynamically added host sends an add host
   request to the master LIM, but master LIM cannot add the host
   for some reason. the slave LIM tries again.
   LSF_MAX_TRY_ADD_HOST specifies how many times the slave LIM
   retries the add host request before giving up.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   20
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MC_NON_PRIVILEGED_PORTS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MC_NON_PRIVILEGED_PORTS=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   MultiCluster only. If this parameter is enabled in one
   cluster, it must be enabled in all clusters.
.sp 2
   Specify Y to make LSF daemons use non-privileged ports for
   communication across clusters.
.sp 2 .SH "Compatibility"
\fBCompatibility\fR
.sp 2
   This disables privileged port daemon authentication, which is
   a security feature. If security is a concern, you should use
   eauth for LSF daemon authentication (see LSF_AUTH_DAEMONS in
   lsf.conf).
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF daemons use privileged port authentication
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MONITOR_LICENSE_TOOL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MONITOR_LICENSE_TOOL=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specify Y to enable data collection by lim for the command
   option lsadmin lsflic.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. lim ignores requests from lsadmin, closing the
   channel.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_MISC\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_MISC=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Directory in which miscellaneous machine independent files,
   such as example source programs and scripts, are installed.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_CONFDIR/misc
.sp 2
\fBLSF_NIOS_DEBUG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_NIOS_DEBUG=1\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Turns on NIOS debugging for interactive jobs.
.sp 2
   If LSF_NIOS_DEBUG=1, NIOS debug messages are written to
   standard error.
.sp 2
   This parameter can also be defined as an environment variable.
.sp 2
   When LSF_NIOS_DEBUG and LSF_CMD_LOGDIR are defined, NIOS debug
   messages are logged in nios.log.\fIhost_name\fR. in the
   location specified by LSF_CMD_LOGDIR.
.sp 2
   If LSF_NIOS_DEBUG is defined, and the directory defined by
   LSF_CMD_LOGDIR is inaccessible, NIOS debug messages are logged
   to /tmp/nios.log.\fIhost_name\fR instead of stderr.
.sp 2
   On Windows, NIOS debug messages are also logged to the
   temporary directory.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_CMD_LOGDIR, LSF_CMD_LOG_MASK, LSF_LOG_MASK, LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_NIOS_JOBSTATUS_INTERVAL\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_NIOS_JOBSTATUS_INTERVAL=\fR\fItime_minutes\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Applies only to interactive batch jobs.
.sp 2
   Time interval at which NIOS polls mbatchd to check if a job is
   still running. Used to retrieve a job’s exit status in the
   case of an abnormal exit of NIOS, due to a network failure for
   example.
.sp 2
   Use this parameter if you run interactive jobs and you have
   scripts that depend on an exit code being returned.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is not defined and a network connection is
   lost, mbatchd cannot communicate with NIOS and the return code
   of a job is not retrieved.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is defined, before exiting, NIOS polls
   mbatchd on the interval defined by LSF_NIOS_JOBSTATUS_INTERVAL
   to check if a job is still running. NIOS continues to poll
   mbatchd until it receives an exit code or mbatchd responds
   that the job does not exist (if the job has already been
   cleaned from memory for example).
.sp 2
   If an exit code cannot be retrieved, NIOS generates an error
   message and the code -11.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Any integer greater than zero
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "Notes"
\fBNotes\fR
.sp 2
   Set this parameter to large intervals such as 15 minutes or
   more so that performance is not negatively affected if
   interactive jobs are pending for too long. NIOS always calls
   mbatchd on the defined interval to confirm that a job is still
   pending and this may add load to mbatchd.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   Environment variable LSF_NIOS_PEND_TIMEOUT
.sp 2
\fBLSF_NIOS_MAX_TASKS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_NIOS_MAX_TASKS=\fR\fIinteger\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the maximum number of NIOS tasks.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_NIOS_RES_HEARTBEAT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_NIOS_RES_HEARTBEAT=\fR\fItime_minutes\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Applies only to interactive non-parallel batch jobs.
.sp 2
   Defines how long NIOS waits before sending a message to RES to
   determine if the connection is still open.
.sp 2
   Use this parameter to ensure NIOS exits when a network failure
   occurs instead of waiting indefinitely for notification that a
   job has been completed. When a network connection is lost, RES
   cannot communicate with NIOS and as a result, NIOS does not
   exit.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is defined, if there has been no
   communication between RES and NIOS for the defined period of
   time, NIOS sends a message to RES to see if the connection is
   still open. If the connection is no longer available, NIOS
   exits.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Any integer greater than zero
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "Notes"
\fBNotes\fR
.sp 2
   The time you set this parameter to depends how long you want
   to allow NIOS to wait before exiting. Typically, it can be a
   number of hours or days. Too low a number may add load to the
   system.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_NON_PRIVILEGED_PORTS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_NON_PRIVILEGED_PORTS=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Disables privileged ports usage.
.sp 2
   By default, LSF daemons and clients running under root account
   use privileged ports to communicate with each other. Without
   LSF_NON_PRIVILEGED_PORTS defined, and if LSF_AUTH is not
   defined in lsf.conf, LSF daemons check privileged port of
   request message to do authentication.
.sp 2
   If LSF_NON_PRIVILEGED_PORTS=Y is defined, LSF clients (LSF
   commands and daemons) do not use privileged ports to
   communicate with daemons and LSF daemons do not check
   privileged ports of incoming requests to do authentication.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PAM_APPL_CHKPNT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSF_PAM_APPL_CHKPNT=Y | N
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When set to Y, allows PAM to function together with
   application checkpointing support.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Y
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PAM_CLEAN_JOB_DELAY\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PAM_CLEAN_JOB_DELAY=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The number of seconds LSF waits before killing a parallel job
   with failed tasks. Specifying LSF_PAM_CLEAN_JOB_DELAY implies
   that if any parallel tasks fail, the entire job should exit
   without running the other tasks in the job. The job is killed
   if any task exits with a non-zero exit code.
.sp 2
   Specify a value greater than or equal to zero (0).
.sp 2
   Applies only to PAM jobs.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Undefined: LSF kills the job immediately
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PAM_HOSTLIST_USE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PAM_HOSTLIST_USE=unique\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Used to start applications that use both OpenMP and MPI.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   unique
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "Notes"
\fBNotes\fR
.sp 2
   At job submission, LSF reserves the correct number of
   processors and PAM starts only 1 process per host. For
   example, to reserve 32 processors and run on 4 processes per
   host, resulting in the use of 8 hosts:
.sp 2
   bsub -n 32 -R "span[ptile=4]" pam yourOpenMPJob
.sp 2 .SH "Where defined"
\fBWhere defined\fR
.sp 2
   This parameter can alternatively be set as an environment
   variable. For example:
.sp 2
   setenv LSF_PAM_HOSTLIST_USE unique
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PAM_PLUGINDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PAM_PLUGINDIR=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The path to libpamvcl.so. Used with Platform LSF HPC.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Path to LSF_LIBDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PAM_USE_ASH\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PAM_USE_ASH=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables LSF to use the SGI IRIX Array Session Handles (ASH) to
   propagate signals to the parallel jobs.
.sp 2
   See the IRIX system documentation and the
   \fRarray_session\fR(\fR5\fR) man page for more information
   about array sessions.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PIM_INFODIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PIM_INFODIR=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The path to where PIM writes the pim.info.host_name file.
.sp 2
   Specifies the path to where the process information is stored.
   The process information resides in the file
   pim.info.host_name. The PIM also reads this file when it
   starts so that it can accumulate the resource usage of dead
   processes for existing process groups.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_PIM_INFODIR
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. The system uses /tmp.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The reporting period for PIM.
.sp 2
   PIM updates the process information every 15 seconds unless an
   application queries this information. If an application
   requests the information, PIM updates the process information
   every LSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME seconds. If the information is not
   queried by any application for more than 5 minutes, the PIM
   reverts back to the 15 second update period.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_PIM_SLEEPTIME
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   15 seconds
.sp 2
\fBLSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME_UPDATE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME_UPDATE=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   UNIX only.
.sp 2
   Use this parameter to improve job throughput and reduce a
   job’s start time if there are many jobs running simultaneously
   on a host. This parameter reduces communication traffic
   between sbatchd and PIM on the same host.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is not defined or set to n, sbatchd
   queries PIM as needed for job process information.
.sp 2
   When this parameter is defined, sbatchd does not query PIM
   immediately as it needs information; sbatchd only queries PIM
   every LSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME seconds.
.sp 2 .SH "Limitations"
\fBLimitations\fR
.sp 2
   When this parameter is defined:
.sp 2
     o  
         sbatchd may be intermittently unable to retrieve process
         information for jobs whose run time is smaller than
         LSF_PIM_SLEEPTIME.
.sp 2
     o  
         It may take longer to view resource usage with bjobs -l.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_PIM_SLEEPTIME_UPDATE
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_POE_TIMEOUT_BIND\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_POE_TIMEOUT_BIND=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the time in seconds for the poe_w wrapper to keep
   trying to set up a server socket to listen on.
.sp 2
   poe_w is the wrapper for the IBM poe driver program.
.sp 2
   LSF_POE_TIMEOUT_BIND can also be set as an environment
   variable for poe_w to read.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   120 seconds
.sp 2
\fBLSF_POE_TIMEOUT_SELECT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_POE_TIMEOUT_SELECT=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the time in seconds for the poe_w wrapper to wait
   for connections from the pmd_w wrapper. pmd_w is the wrapper
   for pmd (IBM PE Partition Manager Daemon).
.sp 2
   LSF_POE_TIMEOUT_SELECT can also be set as an environment
   variable for poe_w to read.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   160 seconds
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_ACCT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_ACCT=\fR\fItime_milliseconds \fR| 0
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If this parameter is defined, RES logs information for
   completed and failed tasks by default (see lsf.acct).
.sp 2
   The value for LSF_RES_ACCT is specified in terms of consumed
   CPU time (milliseconds). Only tasks that have consumed more
   than the specified CPU time are logged.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is defined as LSF_RES_ACCT=0, then all tasks
   are logged.
.sp 2
   For those tasks that consume the specified amount of CPU time,
   RES generates a record and appends the record to the task log
   file lsf.acct.host_name. This file is located in the
   LSF_RES_ACCTDIR directory.
.sp 2
   If this parameter is not defined, the LSF administrator must
   use the lsadmin command (see lsadmin) to turn task logging on
   after RES has started.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_RES_ACCTDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_ACCTDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_ACCTDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The directory in which the RES task log file
   lsf.acct.\fIhost_name\fR is stored.
.sp 2
   If LSF_RES_ACCTDIR is not defined, the log file is stored in
   the /tmp directory.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   (UNIX)/tmp
.sp 2
   (Windows) C:\\temp
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_RES_ACCT
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_ACTIVE_TIME\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_ACTIVE_TIME=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Time in seconds before LIM reports that RES is down.
.sp 2 .SH "Minimum value"
\fBMinimum value\fR
.sp 2
   10 seconds
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   90 seconds
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_CLIENT_TIMEOUT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSF_RES_CLIENT_TIMEOUT=time_minutes
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies in minutes how long an application RES waits for a
   new task before exiting.
.sp 2
      \fBCAUTION: \fR
.sp 2
         If you use the LSF API to run remote tasks and you
         define this parameter with timeout. the remote execution
         of the new task fails (for example, ls_rtask()).
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   The parameter is not set; the application RES waits
   indefinitely for new task to come until client tells it to
   quit.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_CONNECT_RETRY\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_CONNECT_RETRY=\fR\fIinteger | \fR\fR0\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The number of attempts by RES to reconnect to NIOS.
.sp 2
   If LSF_RES_CONNECT_RETRY is not defined, the default value is
   used.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   0
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_NIOS_RES_HEARTBEAT
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_DEBUG\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_DEBUG=1\fR\fI | \fR\fR2\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Sets RES to debug mode.
.sp 2
   If LSF_RES_DEBUG is defined, the Remote Execution Server (RES)
   operates in single user mode. No security checking is
   performed, so RES should not run as root. RES does not look in
   the services database for the RES service port number.
   Instead, it uses port number 36002 unless LSF_RES_PORT has
   been defined.
.sp 2
   Specify 1 for this parameter unless you are testing RES.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_RES_DEBUG=1
.sp 2
   RES runs in the background with no associated control
   terminal.
.sp 2
   LSF_RES_DEBUG=2
.sp 2
   RES runs in the foreground and prints error messages to
   \fRtty\fR.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIM_DEBUG, LSF_CMD_LOGDIR, LSF_CMD_LOG_MASK, LSF_LOG_MASK,
   LSF_LOGDIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_PORT\fR
.sp 2
   See LSF_LIM_PORT, LSF_RES_PORT, LSB_MBD_PORT, LSB_SBD_PORT.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_RLIMIT_UNLIM\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_RLIMIT_UNLIM=cpu\fR | \fRfsize\fR | \fRdata\fR |
   \fRstack\fR | \fRcore\fR | \fRvmem\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   By default, RES sets the hard limits for a remote task to be
   the same as the hard limits of the local process. This
   parameter specifies those hard limits which are to be set to
   unlimited, instead of inheriting those of the local process.
.sp 2
   Valid values are cpu, fsize, data, stack, core, and vmem, for
   CPU, file size, data size, stack, core size, and virtual
   memory limits, respectively.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   The following example sets the CPU, core size, and stack hard
   limits to be unlimited for all remote tasks:
.sp 2
   LSF_RES_RLIMIT_UNLIM="cpu core stack"
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RES_TIMEOUT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RES_TIMEOUT=\fR\fItime_seconds\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Timeout when communicating with RES.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   15
.sp 2
\fBLSF_ROOT_REX\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_ROOT_REX=local\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   UNIX only.
.sp 2
   Allows root remote execution privileges (subject to
   identification checking) on remote hosts, for both interactive
   and batch jobs. Causes RES to accept requests from the
   superuser (root) on remote hosts, subject to identification
   checking.
.sp 2
   If LSF_ROOT_REX is not defined, remote execution requests from
   user root are refused.
.sp 2 .SH "Theory"
\fBTheory\fR
.sp 2
   Sites that have separate root accounts on different hosts
   within the cluster should not define LSF_ROOT_REX. Otherwise,
   this setting should be based on local security policies.
.sp 2
   The lsf.conf file is host-type specific and not shared across
   different platforms. You must make sure that lsf.conf for all
   your host types are changed consistently.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. Root execution is not allowed.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_TIME_CMD, LSF_AUTH
.sp 2
\fBLSF_RSH\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_RSH=\fR\fIcommand\fR [\fIcommand_options\fR]
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies shell commands to use when the following LSF
   commands require remote execution:
.sp 2
     o  
         badmin hstartup
.sp 2
     o  
         bpeek
.sp 2
     o  
         lsadmin limstartup
.sp 2
     o  
         lsadmin resstartup
.sp 2
     o  
         lsfrestart
.sp 2
     o  
         lsfshutdown
.sp 2
     o  
         lsfstartup
.sp 2
     o  
         lsrcpu
.sp 2
   By default, rsh is used for these commands. Use LSF_RSH to
   enable support for ssh.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_RSH
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   To use an ssh command before trying rsh for LSF commands,
   specify:
.sp 2
   LSF_RSH="ssh -o 'PasswordAuthentication no' -o 'StrictHostKeyChecking no'"
.sp 2
   ssh options such as PasswordAuthentication and
   StrictHostKeyChecking can also be configured in the global
   SSH_ETC/ssh_config file or $HOME/.ssh/config.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   ssh, ssh_config
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SECUREDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SECUREDIR=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Windows only; mandatory if using lsf.sudoers.
.sp 2
   Path to the directory that contains the file lsf.sudoers
   (shared on an NTFS file system).
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SERVER_HOSTS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SERVER_HOSTS="\fR\fIhost_name\fR ...\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Defines one or more server hosts that the client should
   contact to find a Load Information Manager (LIM). LSF server
   hosts are hosts that run LSF daemons and provide
   loading-sharing services. Client hosts are hosts that only run
   LSF commands or applications but do not provide services to
   any hosts.
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         LSF_SERVER_HOSTS is required for non-shared slave hosts.
.sp 2
   Use this parameter to ensure that commands execute
   successfully when no LIM is running on the local host, or when
   the local LIM has just started. The client contacts the LIM on
   one of the LSF_SERVER_HOSTS and execute the command, provided
   that at least one of the hosts defined in the list has a LIM
   that is up and running.
.sp 2
   If LSF_SERVER_HOSTS is not defined, the client tries to
   contact the LIM on the local host.
.sp 2
   The host names in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS must be enclosed in quotes
   and separated by white space. For example:
.sp 2
   LSF_SERVER_HOSTS="hostA hostD hostB"
.sp 2
   The parameter string can include up to 4094 characters for
   UNIX or 255 characters for Windows.
.sp 2 .SH "Interaction with LSF_MASTER_LIST"
\fBInteraction with LSF_MASTER_LIST\fR
.sp 2
   Starting in LSF 7, LSF_MASTER_LIST must be defined in
   lsf.conf. You can use the same list of hosts, or a subset of
   the master host list, in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS. If you include the
   primary master host in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS, you should define it
   as the last host of the list.
.sp 2
   If LSF_ADD_CLIENTS is defined in install.config at
   installation, lsfinstall automatically appends the hosts in
   LSF_MASTER_LIST to the list of hosts in LSF_SERVER_HOSTS so
   that the primary master host is last. For example:
.sp 2
   LSF_MASTER_LIST="lsfmaster hostE"
.sp 2
   LSF_SERVER_HOSTS="hostB hostC hostD hostE lsfmaster"
.sp 2
   LSF_ADD_CLIENTS="clientHostA"
.sp 2
   The value of LSF_SERVER_HOSTS is not changed during upgrade.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_MASTER_LIST
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SERVERDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SERVERDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Directory in which all server binaries and shell scripts are
   installed.
.sp 2
   These include lim, res, nios, sbatchd, mbatchd, and mbschd. If
   you use elim, eauth, eexec, esub, etc, they are also installed
   in this directory.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_MACHDEP/etc
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_ECHKPNT_METHOD_DIR
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SHELL_AT_USERS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SHELL_AT_USERS="\fR\fIuser_name user_name \fR...\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Applies to lstcsh only. Specifies users who are allowed to use
   \fR@\fR for host redirection. Users not specified with this
   parameter cannot use host redirection in lstcsh. To specify a
   Windows user account, include the domain name in uppercase
   letters (\fIDOMAIN_NAME\fR\\\fIuser_name\fR).
.sp 2
   If this parameter is not defined, all users are allowed to use
   \fR@\fR for host redirection in lstcsh.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SHIFT_JIS_INPUT\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SHIFT_JIS_INPUT=y\fR | \fRn\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables LSF to accept Shift-JIS character encoding for job
   information (for example, user names, queue names, job names,
   job group names, project names, commands and arguments, esub
   parameters, external messages, etc.)
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   n
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SLURM_DISABLE_CLEANUP\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SLURM_DISABLE_CLEANUP=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Disables cleanup of non-LSF jobs running in a SLURM LSF
   partition on a SLURM cluster.
.sp 2
   By default, only LSF jobs are allowed to run within a SLURM
   LSF partition. LSF periodically cleans up any jobs submitted
   outside of LSF. This clean up period is defined through
   LSB_RLA_UPDATE.
.sp 2
   For example, the following srun job is not submitted through
   LSF, so it is terminated:
.sp 2
   srun -n 4 -p lsf sleep 100000
.sp 2
   srun: error: n13: task[0-1]: Terminated
.sp 2
   srun: Terminating job
.sp 2
   If LSF_SLURM_DISABLE_CLEANUP=Y is set, this job would be
   allowed to run.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_SLURM_TMPDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_SLURM_TMPDIR=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the LSF HPC tmp directory for SLURM clusters. The
   default LSF_TMPDIR /tmp cannot be shared across nodes, so
   LSF_SLURM_TMPDIR must specify a path that is accessible on all
   SLURM nodes.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   /hptc_cluster/lsf/tmp
.sp 2
\fBLSF_STRICT_CHECKING\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_STRICT_CHECKING=Y\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   If set, enables more strict checking of communications between
   LSF daemons and between LSF commands and daemons when LSF is
   used in an untrusted environment, such as a public network
   like the Internet.
.sp 2
   If you enable this parameter, you must enable it in the entire
   cluster, as it affects all communications within LSF. If it is
   used in a MultiCluster environment, it must be enabled in all
   clusters, or none. Ensure that all binaries and libraries are
   upgraded to LSF Version 7, including LSF_BINDIR, LSF_SERVERDIR
   and LSF_LIBDIR directories, if you enable this parameter.
.sp 2
   If your site uses any programs that use the LSF base and batch
   APIs, or LSF MPI (Message Passing Interface), they need to be
   recompiled using the LSF Version 7 APIs before they can work
   properly with this option enabled.
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         You must shut down the entire cluster before enabling or
         disabling this parameter.
.sp 2
         If LSF_STRICT_CHECKING is defined, and your cluster has
         slave hosts that are dynamically added,
         LSF_STRICT_CHECKING must be configured in the local
         lsf.conf on all slave hosts.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid value"
\fBValid value\fR
.sp 2
   Set to Y to enable this feature.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. LSF is secure in trusted environments.
.sp 2
\fBLSF_STRICT_RESREQ\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_STRICT_RESREQ=Y\fR | \fRN\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   When LSF_STRICT_RESREQ=Y, the resource requirement selection
   string must conform to the stricter resource requirement
   syntax described in Administering Platform LSF. The strict
   resource requirement syntax only applies to the select
   section. It does not apply to the other resource requirement
   sections (order, rusage, same, span, or cu).
.sp 2
   When LSF_STRICT_RESREQ=Y in lsf.conf, LSF rejects resource
   requirement strings where an rusage section contains a
   non-consumable resource.
.sp 2
   When LSF_STRICT_RESREQ=N, the default resource requirement
   selection string evaluation is performed.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   N
.sp 2
\fBLSF_STRIP_DOMAIN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_STRIP_DOMAIN=\fR\fIdomain_suffix\fR[\fR:\fR\fIdomain_suffix
   ...\fR]
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   (Optional) If all of the hosts in your cluster can be reached
   using short host names, you can configure LSF to use the short
   host names by specifying the portion of the domain name to
   remove. If your hosts are in more than one domain or have more
   than one domain name, you can specify more than one domain
   suffix to remove, separated by a colon (:).
.sp 2
   For example, given this definition of LSF_STRIP_DOMAIN,
.sp 2
   LSF_STRIP_DOMAIN=.foo.com:.bar.com
.sp 2
   LSF accepts \fRhostA\fR, \fRhostA.foo.com\fR, and
   \fRhostA.bar.com\fR as names for host \fRhostA\fR, and uses
   the name \fRhostA\fR in all output. The leading period ‘.’ is
   required.
.sp 2
   Example:
.sp 2
   LSF_STRIP_DOMAIN=.platform.com:.generic.com
.sp 2
   In the above example, LSF accepts \fRhostA\fR,
   \fRhostA.platform.com\fR, and \fRhostA.generic.com\fR as names
   for \fRhostA\fR, and uses the name \fRhostA\fR in all output.
.sp 2
   Setting this parameter only affects host names displayed
   through LSF, it does not affect DNS host lookup.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_STRIP_DOMAIN
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_TIME_CMD\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_TIME_CMD=\fR\fItimimg_level\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The timing level for checking how long LSF commands run. Time
   usage is logged in milliseconds. Specify a positive integer.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_TIME_MBD, LSB_TIME_SBD, LSB_TIME_CMD, LSF_TIME_LIM,
   LSF_TIME_RES
.sp 2
\fBLSF_TIME_LIM\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_TIME_LIM=\fR\fItiming_level\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The timing level for checking how long LIM routines run.
.sp 2
   Time usage is logged in milliseconds. Specify a positive
   integer.
.sp 2 .SH "EGO parameter"
\fBEGO parameter\fR
.sp 2
   EGO_TIME_LIM
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_TIME_CMD, LSB_TIME_MBD, LSB_TIME_SBD, LSF_TIME_RES
.sp 2
\fBLSF_TIME_RES\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_TIME_RES=\fR\fItiming_level\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The timing level for checking how long RES routines run.
.sp 2
   Time usage is logged in milliseconds. Specify a positive
   integer.
.sp 2
   LSF_TIME_RES is not supported on Windows.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSB_TIME_CMD, LSB_TIME_MBD, LSB_TIME_SBD, LSF_TIME_LIM
.sp 2
\fBLSF_TMPDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_TMPDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Specifies the path and directory for temporary job output.
.sp 2
   When LSF_TMPDIR is defined in lsf.conf, LSF creates a
   temporary directory under the directory specified by
   LSF_TMPDIR on the execution host when a job is started and
   sets the temporary directory environment variable (TMPDIR) for
   the job.
.sp 2
   The name of the temporary directory has the following format:
.sp 2
   $LSF_TMPDIR/job_ID.tmpdir
.sp 2
   On UNIX, the directory has the permission 0700 and is owned by
   the execution user.
.sp 2
   After adding LSF_TMPDIR to lsf.conf, use badmin hrestart all
   to reconfigure your cluster.
.sp 2
   If LSB_SET_TMPDIR= Y, the environment variable TMPDIR will be
   set equal to the path specified by LSF_TMPDIR.
.sp 2
   If the path specified by LSF_TMPDIR does not exist, the value
   of TMPDIR is set to the default path /tmp/\fIjob_ID\fR.tmpdir.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   Specify any valid path up to a maximum length of 256
   characters. The 256 character maximum path length includes the
   temporary directories and files that the system creates as
   jobs run. The path that you specify for LSF_TMPDIR should be
   as short as possible to avoid exceeding this limit.
.sp 2 .SH "UNIX"
\fBUNIX\fR
.sp 2
   Specify an absolute path. For example:
.sp 2
   LSF_TMPDIR=/usr/share/lsf_tmp
.sp 2 .SH "Windows"
\fBWindows\fR
.sp 2
   Specify a UNC path or a path with a drive letter. For example:
.sp 2
   LSF_TMPDIR=\\\\HostA\\temp\\lsf_tmp
.sp 2
   LSF_TMPDIR=D:\\temp\\lsf_tmp
.sp 2 .SH "Temporary directory for tasks launched by blaunch"
\fBTemporary directory for tasks launched by blaunch\fR
.sp 2
   By default, LSF creates a temporary directory for a job only
   on the first execution host. If LSF_TMPDIR is set in lsf.conf,
   the path of the job temporary directory on the first execution
   host is set to LSF_TMPDIR/\fIjob_ID\fR.tmpdir.
.sp 2
   If LSB_SET_TMPDIR= Y, the environment variable TMPDIR will be
   set equal to the path specified by LSF_TMPDIR.
.sp 2
   Tasks launched through the blaunch distributed application
   framework make use of the LSF temporary directory specified by
   LSF_TMPDIR:
.sp 2
     o  
         When the environment variable TMPDIR is set on the first
         execution host, the blaunch framework propagates this
         environment variable to all execution hosts when
         launching remote tasks
.sp 2
     o  
         The job RES or the task RES creates the directory
         specified by TMPDIR if it does not already exist before
         starting the job
.sp 2
     o  
         The directory created by the job RES or task RES has
         permission 0700 and is owned by the execution user
.sp 2
     o  
         If the TMPDIR directory was created by the task RES, LSF
         deletes the temporary directory and its contents when
         the task is complete
.sp 2
     o  
         If the TMPDIR directory was created by the job RES, LSF
         will delete the temporary directory and its contents
         when the job is done
.sp 2
     o  
         If the TMPDIR directory is on a shared file system, it
         is assumed to be shared by all the hosts allocated to
         the blaunch job, so LSF \fIdoes not\fR remove TMPDIR
         directories created by the job RES or task RES
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   By default, LSF_TMPDIR is not enabled. If LSF_TMPDIR is not
   specified in lsf.conf, this parameter is defined as follows:
.sp 2
     o  
         On UNIX: $TMPDIR/\fIjob_ID\fR.tmpdir or
         /tmp/\fIjob_ID\fR.tmpdir
.sp 2
     o  
         On Windows: %TMP%, %TEMP, or %SystemRoot%
.sp 2
\fBLSF_ULDB_DOMAIN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_ULDB_DOMAIN="\fR\fIdomain_name ...\fR\fR"\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_ULDB_DOMAIN specifies the name of the LSF domain in the
   ULDB domain directive. A domain definition of name
   \fIdomain_name\fR must be configured in the SGI IRIX jlimit.in
   input file.
.sp 2
   Used with IRIX User Limits Database (ULDB). Configures LSF so
   that jobs submitted to a host with the IRIX job limits option
   installed are subject to the job limits configured in the IRIX
   User Limits Database (ULDB).
.sp 2
   The ULDB contains job limit information that system
   administrators use to control access to a host on a per user
   basis. The job limits in the ULDB override the system default
   values for both job limits and process limits. When a ULDB
   domain is configured, the limits are enforced as IRIX job
   limits.
.sp 2
   If the ULDB domain specified in LSF_ULDB_DOMAIN is not valid
   or does not exist, LSF uses the limits defined in the domain
   named batch. If the batch domain does not exist, then the
   system default limits are set.
.sp 2
   When an LSF job is submitted, an IRIX job is created, and the
   job limits in the ULDB are applied.
.sp 2
   Next, LSF resource usage limits are enforced for the IRIX job
   under which the LSF job is running. LSF limits override the
   corresponding IRIX job limits. The ULDB limits are used for
   any LSF limits that are not defined. If the job reaches the
   IRIX job limits, the action defined in the IRIX system is
   used.
.sp 2
   IRIX job limits in the ULDB apply only to batch jobs.
.sp 2
   See the IRIX resource administration documentation for
   information about configuring ULDB domains in the jlimit.in
   file.
.sp 2 .SH "LSF resource usage limits controlled by ULDB"
\fBLSF resource usage limits controlled by ULDB\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         PROCESSLIMIT:  Corresponds to IRIX JLIMIT_NUMPROC;
         fork() fails, but the existing processes continue to run
.sp 2
     o  
         MEMLIMIT :  Corresponds to JLIMIT_RSS; Resident pages
         above the limit become prime swap candidates
.sp 2
     o  
         DATALIMIT :  Corresponds to LIMIT_DATA; malloc() calls
         in the job fail with errno set to ENOMEM
.sp 2
     o  
         CPULIMIT:  Corresponds to JLIMIT_CPU; IRIX sends SIGXCPU
         signal to job, then after the grace period expires,
         sends SIGINT, SIGTERM, and SIGKILL
.sp 2
     o  
         FILELIMIT:  No corresponding IRIX limit; use process
         limit RLIMIT_FSIZE
.sp 2
     o  
         STACKLIMIT :  No corresponding IRIX limit; use process
         limit RLIMIT_STACK
.sp 2
     o  
         CORELIMIT:  No corresponding IRIX limit; use process
         limit RLIMIT_CORE
.sp 2
     o  
         SWAPLIMIT:  Corresponds to JLIMIT_VMEM; use process
         limit RLIMIT_VMEM
.sp 2 .SH "Increasing the default MEMLIMIT for ULDB"
\fBIncreasing the default MEMLIMIT for ULDB\fR
.sp 2
   In some pre-defined LSF queues, such as normal, the default
   MEMLIMIT is set to 5000 (5 MB). However, if ULDB is enabled
   (LSF_ULDB_DOMAIN is defined) the MEMLIMIT should be set
   greater than 8000 in lsb.queues.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBLSF_UNIT_FOR_LIMITS\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_UNIT_FOR_LIMITS=\fR\fIunit\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables scaling of large units in resource usage limits.
.sp 2
   When set, LSF_UNIT_FOR_LIMITS applies cluster-wide to limits
   at the job-level (bsub), queue-level (lsb.queues), and
   application level (lsb.applications).
.sp 2
   The limit unit specified by LSF_UNIT_FOR_LIMITS also applies
   to limits modified with bmod, and the display of resource
   usage limits in query commands (bacct, bapp, bhist, bhosts,
   bjobs, bqueues, lsload, and lshosts).
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         Before changing the units of your resource usage limits,
         you should completely drain the cluster of all workload.
         There should be no running, pending, or finished jobs in
         the system.
.sp 2
   In a MultiCluster environment, you should configure the same
   unit for all clusters.
.sp 2 .SH "Example"
\fBExample\fR
.sp 2
   A job is submitted with bsub -M 100 and
   LSF_UNIT_FOR_LIMITS=MB; the memory limit for the job is 100 MB
   rather than the default 100 KB.
.sp 2 .SH "Valid values"
\fBValid values\fR
.sp 2
   \fIunit\fR indicates the unit for the resource usage limit,
   one of:
.sp 2
     o  
         KB (kilobytes)
.sp 2
     o  
         MB (megabytes)
.sp 2
     o  
         GB (gigabytes)
.sp 2
     o  
         TB (terabytes)
.sp 2
     o  
         PB (petabytes)
.sp 2
     o  
         EB (exabytes)
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   KB
.sp 2
\fBLSF_USE_HOSTEQUIV\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_USE_HOSTEQUIV=y\fR | \fRY\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   (UNIX only; optional)
.sp 2
   If LSF_USE_HOSTEQUIV is defined, RES and mbatchd call the
   \fRruserok()\fR function to decide if a user is allowed to run
   remote jobs.
.sp 2
   The \fRruserok()\fR function checks in the /etc/hosts.equiv
   file and the user’s $HOME/.rhosts file to decide if the user
   has permission to execute remote jobs.
.sp 2
   If LSF_USE_HOSTEQUIV is not defined, all normal users in the
   cluster can execute remote jobs on any host.
.sp 2
   If LSF_ROOT_REX is set, root can also execute remote jobs with
   the same permission test as for normal users.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_ROOT_REX
.sp 2
\fBLSF_USER_DOMAIN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
LSF_USER_DOMAIN=domain_name:domain_name:domain_name... .
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   Enables the UNIX/Windows user account mapping feature, which
   allows cross-platform job submission and execution in a mixed
   UNIX/Windows environment. LSF_USER_DOMAIN specifies one or
   more Windows domains that LSF either strips from the user
   account name when a job runs on a UNIX host, or adds to the
   user account name when a job runs on a Windows host.
.sp 2
      \fBImportant: \fR
.sp 2
         Configure \fBLSF_USER_DOMAIN\fR immediately after you
         install LSF; changing this parameter in an existing
         cluster requires that you verify and possibly
         reconfigure service accounts, user group memberships,
         and user passwords.
.sp 2
   Specify one or more Windows domains, separated by a colon (:).
   You can enter an unlimited number of Windows domains. A period
   (.) specifies a local account, not a domain.
.sp 2 .SH "Examples"
\fBExamples\fR
.sp 2
   \fBLSF_USER_DOMAIN\fR=BUSINESS
.sp 2
   \fBLSF_USER_DOMAIN\fR=BUSINESS:ENGINEERING:SUPPORT
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   The default depends on your LSF installation:
.sp 2
     o  
         If you upgrade a cluster to LSF version 7, the default
         is the existing value of \fBLSF_USER_DOMAIN\fR, if
         defined
.sp 2
     o  
         For a new cluster, this parameter is not defined, and
         UNIX/Windows user account mapping is not enabled
.sp 2
\fBLSF_VPLUGIN\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRLSF_VPLUGIN=\fR\fIpath\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   The full path to the vendor MPI library libxmpi.so. Used with
   Platform LSF HPC.
.sp 2
   For PAM to access the SGI MPI libxmpi.so library, the file
   permission mode must be 755 (\fR-rwxr-xr-x\fR).
.sp 2 .SH "Examples"
\fBExamples\fR
.sp 2
     o  
         HP MPI: LSF_VPLUGIN=/opt/mpi/lib/pa1.1/libmpirm.sl
.sp 2
     o  
         SGI MPI: LSF_VPLUGIN=/usr/lib32/libxmpi.so
.sp 2
     o  
         SGI Linux (64-bit x-86 Linux 2.6, glibc 2.3.):
         LSF_VPLUGIN=/usr/lib32/libxmpi.so:/usr/lib/libxmpi.so:
         /usr/lib64/libxmpi.so
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined
.sp 2
\fBMC_PLUGIN_REMOTE_RESOURCE\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRMC_PLUGIN_REMOTE_RESOURCE=y\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   MultiCluster job forwarding model only. By default, the
   submission cluster does not consider remote resources. Define
   \fRMC_PLUGIN_REMOTE_RESOURCE=y\fR in the submission cluster to
   allow consideration of remote resources.
.sp 2
      \fBNote: \fR
.sp 2
         When MC_PLUGIN_REMOTE_RESOURCE is defined, only the
         following resource requirements (boolean only) are
         supported: -R "type==type_name", -R "same[type]" and -R
         "defined(resource_name)"
.sp 2
      \fBNote: \fR
.sp 2
         When \fBMC_PLUGIN_SCHEDULE_ENHANCE\fR in lsb.params is
         defined, remote resources are considered as if
         \fRMC_PLUGIN_REMOTE_RESOURCE=Y\fR regardless of the
         actual value. In addition, details of the remote cluster
         workload are considered by the submission cluster
         scheduler.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   Not defined. The submission cluster does not consider remote
   resources.
.sp 2 .SH "See also"
\fBSee also\fR
.sp 2
   \fBMC_PLUGIN_SCHEDULE_ENHANCE\fR in lsb.params
.sp 2
\fBXLSF_APPDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRXLSF_APPDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   (UNIX only; optional) Directory in which X application default
   files for LSF products are installed.
.sp 2
   The LSF commands that use X look in this directory to find the
   application defaults. Users do not need to set environment
   variables to use the Platform LSF X applications. The
   application default files are platform-independent.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_INDEP/misc
.sp 2
\fBXLSF_UIDDIR\fR
.sp 2

.sp 2 .SH "Syntax"
\fBSyntax\fR
.sp 2
   \fRXLSF_UIDDIR=\fR\fIdirectory\fR
.sp 2 .SH "Description"
\fBDescription\fR
.sp 2
   (UNIX only) Directory in which Motif User Interface Definition
   files are stored.
.sp 2
   These files are platform-specific.
.sp 2 .SH "Default"
\fBDefault\fR
.sp 2
   LSF_LIBDIR/uid
